  For example, here is how the depth of weapon effect is 
distributed in the U.S. Army defense in accordance with the 
"air-land operation" concept. A zone of fire of from 1 to 30-40 
km is assigned for artillery, including MLRS, from 10-15 to 
60-70 km for tactical missile systems, from 50-70 to 400-1,000 
km for operational missile systems, up to 300-400 km for J-SAK 
reconnaissance-strike complexes, 300-500 km or more for tactical 
aviation and up to 20-70 km for combat helicopters. 
  The ratio of offensive and defensive weapons now is such 
that 
it permits drawing the conclusion that their opposition will 
take on an especially intensive character. The "fire tenacity" 
of the defense has increased many times and now it is not enough 
to disorganize the artillery-mortar fire plan in order for an 
attacker to be able to dictate his will on the enemy; this 
requires deep engagement of targets, above all precision weapon 
systems--reconnaissance-strike and reconnaissance-fire 
complexes, nuclear attack weapons, combat helicopters, EW 
assets, as well as remote minelaying equipment. 
  We will note that the striving to increase the depth of 
effect on the enemy also was clearly displayed in Soviet troop 
operations in the Great Patriotic War. While the defense was 
suppressed to a depth of 2.5-3 km by massed artillery fire in 
offensive operations of 1941-1942 and to a depth of 3-4 km in 
operations of 1943, during 1944-1945 the depth of simultaneous 
suppression of the enemy defense increased to 6-8 km and in the 
concluding operations it often reached 15 km or 
more.[.sup]48[/] 
  Under present conditions deep fire engagement should take in 
enemy weapons situated both in the tactical as well as 
operational zone of his defense. This is determined by the fact 
that the bulk of enemy weapons are situated at a considerable 
depth from the troops' line of contact. Thus, the experience of 
NATO Allied Forces exercises held in the 1980's showed that 
field artillery firing positions in the defense of formations 
are assigned at a distance of 3-5 km, firing positions of 
artillery employing Copperhead and SADARM guided projectiles 
8-10 km, and MLRS 10-25 km from the FEBA; helicopters with 
jammers operate from zones 10-15 km from the line of contact; 
control centers for J-SAK reconnaissance-strike complexes are 
situated at a distance of 30-50 km, facilities of the TACELIS 
and REMBASS reconnaissance systems at a distance of 30-160 km, 
and loiter zones of aircraft of the PLSS, AWACS and Nimrod 
systems at a distance of 30-160 km from the FEBA.[.sup]49[/] 
  The depth of fire engagement in the offensive increases 
accordingly. American specialists assert that the depth of the 
zone of simultaneous combat effect by organic and attached 
weapons should be 15 km for brigade, 70 km for division, 150 km 
for army corps and 300-500 km or more for army 
group.[.sup]50[/] Within limits of these zones the priority 
in fire engagement is given to continuous fire effect on nuclear 
attack weapons, precision weapon systems, facilities for command 
and control of troops and weapons, and targets of the enemy 
first and second echelons, which creates a precondition for 
disorganizing his fire plan. 
  Decisiveness in the struggle to win fire superiority over 
the 
enemy is manifested in preempting him in delivering deep fire 
strikes. There now are capabilities for this. Integration of 
weapons, reconnaissance equipment and command and control 
equipment in an automated system permits fire damage of the 
enemy in real or near-real time. Thus, adoption of the TACFIRE 
field artillery automated control system in U.S. Army formations 
enabled reducing fire planning time in the division from 2 hours 
to 2 minutes, and fire preparation time in the artillery 
battalion from 30 minutes to 1-2 minutes.[.sup]51[/] 
  J-SAK and PLSS reconnaissance-strike complexes possess even 
greater speed. In a matter of seconds they can detect enemy 
targets, identify them by type, issue a target designation on 
them to appropriate weapons and deliver precise, powerful fire 
strikes against the detected targets, including small moving 
ones. Pave Tiger drones also are used in an automatic mode. They 
perform an automatic search, detection, identification and 
precise destruction of air defense system radars and aircraft 
guidance radars from alert duty zones. 
  In order to achieve decisiveness and high rates in 
conducting 
an attack, it is necessary to achieve a high degree of fire 
damage of various targets in the defense. The Great Patriotic 
War experience showed that in a breakthrough it was necessary to 
destroy as a minimum up to 25 percent and suppress around 30 
percent of various targets situated in the first and second 
positions of the enemy's main defensive zone. That degree of 
fire damage now is no longer enough. 
  Such targets as means of nuclear attack, precision weapon 
systems, and facilities for command and control of troops and 
weapons must be damaged with a degree of up to 100 percent, and 
the other targets with no less a degree than 70-75 percent; 
otherwise the defender may disrupt the attack. 
  A question arises on how to attain such a high degree of 
fire 
damage if the attacker's capabilities for creating high 
artillery densities in a penetration are very limited. The only 
way to increase effectiveness of fire damage of the enemy is to 
achieve the delivery of precise, aimed strikes against targets 
and exclude the "area" suppression method. This will enable a 
significant reduction in numbers of artillery, missile 
launchers, aircraft and helicopters as well as the amount of 
ammunition used for this purpose. 
  Performance of this mission is facilitated by the fact that 
weapon accuracy now has increased sharply. For example, range 
tests showed that employment of Copperhead and SADARM precision 
artillery projectiles permits reducing ammunition expenditure by 
10-15 times. It is also the very same in aviation--use of the 
LAD guided air-dropped clusters enables reducing the expenditure 
of aerial bombs by 4-5 times. 
  An increased power of munitions largely contributes to 
effective performance of the fire damage mission. Based on 
foreign press data, the power of fuel-air explosives used by 
armies of the anti-Iraq coalition during Operation Desert Storm 
(1991) were close to a low-yield nuclear weapon in force. This 
also helps considerably decrease artillery and air densities in 
the offensive. 
  Successfully combating enemy helicopters is a new component 
element of winning fire superiority. At the present time many 
foreign armies view combat helicopters as one of the important 
means of increasing decisiveness and aggressiveness in battle. 
In the defense they are assigned to perform a mission such as 
destroying the attacker's weapons--field artillery, army 
aviation, tanks and EW assets. 
  Combating helicopters presents no small amount of 
difficulty. 
Their operations are characterized by covertness of the target 
approach, swiftness and surprise in delivering a strike, and 
high accuracy of engaging targets at long range without having 
the platform enter the impact zone of air defense weapons. Based 
on the experience of local wars and exercises, helicopters have 
proven themselves to be a highly effective means of combating 
armored targets. For example, a company of helicopters with TOW 
ATGM's is capable of destroying 80-100 tanks in one sortie. 
  In NATO troop exercise strikes by mixed aircraft-helicopter 
elements (ground attack aircraft and strike and reconnaissance 
helicopters) are widely practiced for direct air support of 
combined arms formations. In Operation Desert Storm methods of 
operations were employed, such as successive delivery of strikes 
against tanks and air defense weapons with a lengthy effect on 
the enemy and simultaneous strikes by helicopters, artillery and 
aircraft against one or more targets. 
  Combat practice and exercise experience attest to the fact 
that high helicopter mobility permits combined arms commanders 
to decisively mass fire at the necessary moment against the most 
important targets and transfer it from one axis to another in 
the shortest time periods in order to win and hold fire 
superiority. Concentrated strikes by helicopters usually are 
delivered at the most important moments of battle: Repulse of an 
assault by major tank forces, commitment of a second echelon, 
assault crossing of water obstacles. 
  All this indicates that without successfully combating enemy 
helicopters it is impossible to achieve high decisiveness and 
aggressiveness in offensive battle and the meeting engagement. 
The antihelicopter warfare system is laid down in planning the 
battle and in organizing interworking and comprehensive support. 
Measures taken for this purpose include prompt detection of 
helicopters and warning subunits of the possibility of their 
delivering strikes. The most likely strike delivery lines are 
determined in order to combat enemy helicopters, and necessary 
weapons are assigned for destroying helicopters in concentration 
areas, assembly areas and at tactical positions. Small arms 
fire, particularly antiaircraft machineguns of tank subunits 
when helicopters are in their zone of effective fire, is of no 
small importance in combating helicopters. 
  Skillful choice of effective methods of defeating the enemy 
plays a special role in realizing the principle of decisiveness 
and aggressiveness in the offensive and in the meeting 
engagement. The attacker's attempt to paralyze the defender's 
actions by delivering strikes against him from different 
directions--front, flanks and rear--was observed long ago. Such 
a method enables dissipating enemy forces and creating 
conditions for breaking up his grouping and defeating it in 
detail. But with formation of a continuous static front, such 
conditions in the two world wars were presented to troops 
primarily in a meeting engagement or in the dynamics of combat 
operations, when the attacker employed maneuver and took 
advantage of gaps which had formed and of exposed flanks in the 
enemy combat alignment. 
  In breaking through an enemy defense prepared in advance and 
well fortified in the engineer sense, the attacker was forced to 
methodically "gnaw through" it, gradually grinding down his 
personnel and equipment. Under such conditions mobile operations 
were extremely limited. Still, as the troops' attack potential 
built up, the attacker tried to increase the aggressiveness of 
operations by delivering frontal attacks against the enemy 
across a broad front on a number of axes. But at that time this 
was the prerogative only of the operational echelon. 
  Now the situation has changed. Combined arms formations have 
the capability of employing very decisive methods of defeating 
the enemy, such as delivering splitting attacks from the front 
by forces of tank and motorized rifle units on one or two axes 
in combination with a simultaneous landing of airborne assault 
forces in the enemy rear, and also with swift penetrations by 
mobile units and subunits--forward, enveloping and raiding 
detachments--into the depth of the defense. This permits 
paralyzing the defender's operations, constraining the maneuver 
of his reserves and creating preconditions for their swift 
defeat in detail. 
  In a meeting engagement, when the enemy has exposed flanks, 
a 
combination ground-air strike can be delivered both from the 
front as well as from the flanks. As shown by exercise 
experience, a special effect is produced by a two-sided deep 
envelopment of the enemy with a move into his deep rear in 
combination with operations by a tactical airborne assault force. 
  Speaking of realizing the principle of decisiveness in the 
offensive, one cannot fail to take into account those 
difficulties which arise in this connection, especially in 
overcoming a stable antitank defense. Already in World War II 
the antitank defense was the "backbone" of the entire defense 
system. It was established to the full tactical and operational 
depth. The density of antitank weapons on the most important 
axes reached 20-30 or more. Under present conditions the 
importance of an antitank defense has grown even more and, what 
is especially important, the majority of antitank weapons are 
armored and self-propelled. The number of such targets in 
formations of foreign armies is constantly increasing (Table 3). 


Table 3 - Number of Armored Antitank Weapons in U.S. Divisions[.sup]52[/] 

Antitank          Inf Div      Inf Div      Mech    Mech    Mech    Mech 
Weapons           1945-1954    1954-1960    Div     Div     Div     Div-86 
                                            1967    1972    1985 

Tanks             144          125          254     243     252     290 

ATGM system       -            -            -       -       108     60 
combat vehicle 

