<H3>  CHAPTER FOUR - COORDINATED EMPLOYMENT OF SUBUNITS OF COMBAT 
ARMS AND SPECIAL TROOPS AND MAINTENANCE OF CONTINUOUS 
INTERWORKING AMONG THEM </H3>
[.sup]1[/] 
  Interworking consists of operations by troops 
(forces) coordinated by objective, missions, place, time and 
methods of mission accomplishment for achieving the objective of 
the battle or operation; one of the principles of military 
art. 
  "Voyennyy entsiklopedicheskiy slovar" 
[Military Encyclopedic Dictionary] 
  Interworking and mutual help are the best 
tactics. 
  P. S. Nakhimov 
  All measures prescribed by regulations will 
remain fruitless until all officers and soldiers realize the 
very enormous importance of coherency and uniformity of 
operations. 
  From a digest of tactical instructions given 
by superiors in the war of 1904-1905. 
  There can be no victory in modern battle without 
precise, continuous interworking. 
  R. Ya. Malinovskiy 
<H3>  1. From the History of the Origin and Development of the 
Principle of Interworking </H3>
  The principle of interworking is considered one of the most 
important in all world armies. Many works have been written 
about its importance and essence, and there probably are no 
generalizing directive instructions on troop combat training 
which would not mention interworking in one form or another. 
This also was discussed thoroughly in prewar Red Army Field 
Service Regulations. But when the Great Patriotic War broke out 
it was learned that our commanders and staffs proved to be 
especially poorly trained, specifically in questions of 
coordinating troop combat efforts. They made many 
miscalculations in this matter. 
  A striking gap occurred between word and action, between 
theory and practice. Here is what 22nd Army Commander Lieutenant 
General G. P. Korotkov, who went through the entire war from the 
first to the last shot, said on this score at a 1945 Army 
Military-Science Conference devoted to an analysis of experience 
of combat operations: "There was no regular commander before the 
war who would not have learned the popular aphorism: Without 
interworking there is no victory. But the war began and the 
first and biggest flaws' at all our command echelons showed up 
in coordination of mutual operations of infantry with artillery 
and combat engineers, and of infantrymen with tankers. . . . It 
took almost one and one-half years of stubborn battles for us 
finally to learn to interwork genuinely and aggressively in the 
offensive and the defense." 
  War experience showed that nowhere is the commander's 
tactical competence manifested so clearly and with such 
completeness as in organizing and accomplishing interworking in 
battle. Reflected here as in a mirror are his combat 
proficiency, knowledge of combat capabilities of combat arms, 
ability to use them sensibly in accomplishing combat missions 
and make up for weak aspects of one kind of weapon or combat 
equipment with strong aspects of other kinds, and ability to 
anticipate the development of events and not allow all possible 
chance happenings to perniciously affect the troops. 
Interworking tolerates no amateurishness. Only a comprehensively 
trained, erudite officer is capable of successfully coping with 
this difficult task in a combat situation. 
  The objective of the chapter is to help the officer master 
the art of leading troops; to show in examples how the principle 
of interworking originated and developed since ancient times and 
how and under the influence of what factors its content was 
renewed; and on this basis to develop certain practical 
recommendations and certain advice as to how to implement the 
demands of this principle most expediently in different kinds of 
modern battle. 
  We will note that like other principles of battle, the 
principle of interworking went through two stages in its 
evolution--the stage of the empirical experiment by the 
trial-and-error method and [the stage of] theoretical 
generalizations and development of scientifically substantiated 
provisions on this question. The "Voyennaya entsiklopediya" 
[Military Encyclopedia] aptly put it: "Every area of human 
creativeness (also including military affairs) goes through a 
phase of unconscious art and in the end arrives at a rational 
art having a rather substantiated science (principles, rules, 
forms, norms and so on)."[.sup]2[/] 
  The first step in amassing experience in organizing 
interworking in battle was made in ancient Egypt, Assyria, 
Babylon, China and India. Already during the slaveholding 
formation military historians and thinkers were attempting to 
find recipes for victory, among which, as Euripides noted, was 
the striving to learn to achieve a common goal in different ways. 
  One of the most ancient sources setting forth precepts on 
how 
to prepare and fight a battle and achieve coordination of 
operations is the Chinese "Seven Books," particularly the 
treatise "On the Art of Warfare" by Wu Zi, military theorist and 
field general of ancient China (5th-4th centuries B.C.). It 
notes that one must win in war by the best organization and 
cohesiveness of operations. "If an army obeys a single 
authority," wrote Wu Zi, "and acts in a coordinated way, then 
commanders and soldiers execute orders in battle, there is no 
enemy who could resist, there is no combat formation which could 
stand fast."[.sup]3[/] 
  Coordinated use of four-wheeled war chariots in battle 
together with infantry and cavalry is of interest in combat 
operations by armies of the first states of the Ancient East. 
The chariots were used for operations on an axis where success 
had appeared. By using this mobile means of attack, an army 
could pursue the enemy. It is typical that a missile-throwing 
weapon, the arbalest, appeared for the first time in the ancient 
Chinese army, which enabled engaging the enemy from a distance. 
  Interworking saw substantial development in wars of Ancient 
Greece, Macedonia, Rome and Carthage. It was then that the need 
arose for operations of ground forces to be mutually tied in 
with warships and transport vessels. The presence in the 
inventory of the Greek and Roman armies of rams and siege 
equipment in the form of mobile antifortress towers in 
combination with missile-throwing weapons--catapults and 
ballistas--complicated the nature of battle and permitted 
shifting from a lengthy siege to an assault of fortified 
city-fortresses. As a result of evolution, the battle was 
divided as it were into two stages--preparation of battle and 
its conduct (hand-to-hand fighting). The military leader was 
required to coordinate combat efforts of mixed forces: Infantry, 
cavalry, war chariots, detachments of sappers who performed 
military engineer work, and also the rear service (Fig. 8). 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-54A>             Fig. 8. Battle of Gaugamela </FIG>



  Initial experience in matters of coordinating troop efforts 
found a certain reflection in the following works by ancient 
writers: "Advice for Cavalry Commanders," "Advice for 
Cavalrymen" and "Cyropaedia" by Xenophon; "Tactics" by Aeneas; 
"Tactics" by Asclepiodotus; "Theory of Tactics" by Aelian; "The 
Jugurthine War" by Sallustius Crispus; "Civil War" by Julius 
Caesar; "The Annals" by Cornelius Tacitus; "Stratagems" by 
Julius Frontinus; "Manual for Military Leaders" by Onasander; "A 
Brief Exposition of Principles of Military Affairs" by Vegetius; 
and "Strategikon" by False-Mauricius. 
  An improvement in interworking occurred slowly in the period 
of the Middle Ages. The period of formation of feudal 
relationships in military affairs initially was characterized by 
an absence of precise tactical forms. Outfitted with primitive 
weapons for hand-to-hand combat, an army fought in dense crowds. 
Organizationally it was not broken into subunits. As metal 
weapons and protective gear improved and their numbers 
increased, combat formations of infantry as the main combat arm 
of that time evolved from deep column-like and wedge-like 
formations to formations of the phalanx type that were extended 
laterally and were shallower but were dense and more organized. 
  Eastern Slavs called such a formation a "wall." Lightly 
armed 
infantry (bowmen) and cavalry were intended for conducting 
reconnaissance, engaging, and covering flanks of the "wall." The 
latter decided the outcome of battle by its attack. Subsequent 
development of tactics required breaking up the "wall" both 
laterally as well as in depth. Initially the division of a 
combat formation into three parts (a "shelf row"), and then into 
a larger number of parts appeared in Rus (Fig. 9). In conducting 
battle the regiments--right-hand regiment, left-hand regiment, 
"forehead" (center) regiment, ambuscade force--began to use a 
varying alignment, as a result of which the depth of the 
battlefield increased and maneuver and countermaneuver by 
regiments began to be accomplished more widely. This complicated 
coordination of troop combat efforts. Often it would happen as 
follows: The center regiment, the "forehead," would repel an 
enemy attack from the front and the right-hand and left-hand 
regiments would envelop him from the flanks, as occurred, for 
example, in the Battle on Lake Peipus in 1242. The military 
leader was required to correctly distribute forces to the 
regiments, assign missions for all parts of the combat 
formation, tie their actions together, promptly commit the 
reserve, organize the pursuit and so on. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-55A>             Fig. 9. Troop combat formations of Kievan Rus: </FIG>



  The appearance of firearms in the period of the late Middle 
Ages had a great influence on development of interworking. This 
was manifested in Rus in the fact that a standing army armed 
with firearms was formed already in the middle of the 16th 
century. The "Nakaz ugorskim voyevodam" [Instructions to Ugorsk 
Voevodes] prescribed rehearsing the following tactics of 
fighting the forays by steppe inhabitants: "Divide the 
harquebusiers and pososhnyye by regiments, as many as there must 
be ashore, and the voevodes and their people are to be at the 
ready." It was envisaged that pososhnyye (auxiliary infantry) 
should immobilize the enemy, harquebusiers armed with handheld 
firearms should engage him by fire and in hand-to-hand combat, 
and the noble landed cavalry (boyar children) should exploit 
success. Later the artillery joined these combat arms. Small 
cannons (the "small detail") would cover the actions of 
pososhnyye and harquebusiers and the great cannons (the "large 
detail") would enter battle at a decisive moment. 
  Simultaneously with this, in the 15th-17th centuries 
detachments of craftsmen specialists appeared in the Russian 
Army: "wall builders," who engaged in building fortifications; 
"bridge builders," who built bridges and crossings; and 
"ballista experts," who built siege machines 
(poroks). These were the first predecessors of 
Russian military engineers, sappers and pontonmen. The 
development of artillery lent great impetus to creating special 
engineer subunits inasmuch as, on the one hand, a need appeared 
to accomplish engineer measures to support artillery combat 
operations and, on the other hand, it was necessary to build 
engineer structures for protection against enemy artillery fire 
and other weapons. 
  The role of interworking in battle elevated especially with 
the appearance of mass armies (late 18th-early 19th centuries). 
The nature of combat operations changed and their spatial scope 
increased under the influence of more sophisticated means of 
warfare. Under those conditions the military leader was forced 
to coordinate troop efforts with their deployment across a 
rather broad front, with the use of deep combat formations and 
with fighting on rough terrain. 
  Many new tactics appeared in artillery operations in wars of 
the first half of the 19th century. Artillery was employed for 
splitting enemy combat formations. The principle of massing 
artillery fire was established as a result not only of the use 
of large batteries, but also of the battlefield maneuver of 
pieces. Missions began to be divided among separate artillery 
groups. An artillery reserve was established. Interworking with 
other combat arms acquired great importance.[.sup]4[/] 
  New features of interworking were manifested especially 
clearly in the Patriotic War of 1812, above all in the Battle of 
Borodino. The strong side of Russian troop tactics was that they 
combined the actions of infantry with artillery and cavalry in 
battle more flexibly than did the French. In repelling an 
assault of Napoleon's troops, chasseurs operating in extended 
order would cover strongpoints of artillery batteries making up 
the framework of the entire Russian defense, and line infantry 
together with cavalry would deliver an attack against the 
wedged-in enemy (figs. 10 and 11). 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-56A>             Fig. 10. Battle of Borodino [remainder of caption </FIG>






<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-57A></FIG>



                But the war also identified major shortcomings in 
interworking of infantry with artillery. The fact was that at 
that time the infantry operated primarily in battalion columns 
and it was difficult for it to combine maneuver and attack with 
artillery fire. The chasseurs and artillery used their fire to 
prepare the infantry bayonet attack, but they were incapable of 
giving it fire support during exploitation of success. As a 
result, the striking power of infantry units proved to be 
insufficiently powerful. 
  The experience of the Patriotic War of 1812 showed that 
under 
the altered conditions of battle it was necessary to give 
division and regimental commanders more freedom of actions in 
matters of command and control and coordination of troop combat 
efforts. The time had passed for commanders in chief to draw up 
detailed operation orders which specified subordinates' every 
step for the entire time of the battle. 
  The system of troop interworking in battle developed further 
under the determining influence of the appearance of rifled 
weapons, smokeless powder and high explosives and employment of 
technical communications equipment. New features of interworking 
were clearly manifested in the Franco-Prussian (1870-1871), 
Crimean (1853-1856) and Russo-Turkish (1877-1878) wars. The 
infantry acquired new combat qualities. Armed with rifled 
weapons, it began to possess greater striking power. This 
allowed it not only to strive to defeat the enemy in 
hand-to-hand combat, but also to inflict a loss on him by its 
fire even while closing with him. The increased range of fire of 
artillery and infantry weapons engendered a new, dispersed 
combat formation, the extended line of riflemen. Troops began 
deploying into combat formation at a considerable distance from 
the enemy (Fig. 12). Russian infantry combat formations during 
the Crimean War are shown in Fig. 12. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-58A>             Fig. 12. Russian infantry combat formations during </FIG>
<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-71A>           Fig. 13. Sequence of developing questions ofFigure 1. Artillery Battalion </FIG>



  The role of artillery fire rose. In the Crimean War, for 
example, a new mission began to be assigned to artillery--to 
inflict damage on enemy personnel sheltered in trenches. The 
importance of terrain fortification rose under conditions of 
position warfare. Along with the construction of poured 
earthworks (redoubts, fl&egrave;ches, lunettes), group 
emplacements 
(logements) linked by connecting passages began to be dug and 
protective cover and shelters began being built for reserves. 
The strength of the defense increased considerably through use 
of plain wire obstacles, by the arrangement of knife rests, and 
also by use of fougasses covered by artillery and infantry fire. 
  N. V. Medem's textbook "Taktika" [Tactics] (1837), which set 
forth practical recommendations on how to fight in an extended 
order in combination with column operations, played an important 
role in developing the theory and practice of interworking of 
troops in battle in the Russian Army in the 19th century. The 
textbook examined the influence of terrain conditions and other 
situation elements on the nature of interworking. These 
provisions were later developed in the work by F. I. Goremykin 
"Rukovodstvo k izucheniyu taktiki v nachalnykh yeye osnovaniyakh 
i v prakticheskom primenenii" [Manual for Study of Initial 
Foundations and Practical Application of Tactics] (1849). The 
work gave greatest attention to interworking of infantry with 
artillery. The author pointed out the perniciousness of their 
separate conduct of battle. They should be disposed on the 
battlefield, he advised, in such a way as to have an opportunity 
to help each other without constraining their actions. 
  Questions of interworking held a prominent place in works by 
G. A. Leyer "Metod voyennykh nauk" [Method of Military Sciences] 
and "Strategiya (taktika teatra voyennykh deystviy)" [Strategy 
(Tactics of a Theater of Military Operations)] (Leyer called 
this principle the principle of mutual support) and A. N. Petrov 
"K voprosam strategii" [On Questions of Strategy]. M. I. 
Dragomirov directed attention to the importance of skillful use 
of this principle. He wrote: "Each objective in war is achieved 
more surely by the combined efforts of many directed toward a 
common objective."[.sup]5[/] 
  Many forecasts on how battle would develop were expressed 
prior to World War I. Many military theorists were inclined to 
think that the infantry would continue to play a predominant 
role in it. "The battle chiefly will be the struggle of two 
infantries, and victory will be on the side of the greater 
number of battalions."[.sup]6[/] The reason for such 
erroneous theories was that little consideration was given to 
the intensive development of means of warfare. 
  The essence of changes which occurred in the material basis 
of battle was that the machinegun became a mass weapon of ground 
troops. Field artillery improved. Cannons and howitzers from 
76-mm to 152-mm in caliber became operational. Their combat 
qualities rose substantially as a result of introduction of the 
optical sight. Heavy-caliber pieces also improved, right up to 
the appearance of superpowerful, long-range guns. There was a 
sharp increase in the number of mortars, and flamethrowers 
appeared. The amount of artillery increased by 6-8 times in the 
army compared with wars of the latter half of the 19th century. 
Creation of the armored vehicle and especially the tank (1916) 
became a major step in armament development. Aircraft saw 
quantitative and qualitative development in the course of the 
war. 
  Under the influence of this, the battle assumed a combined 
arms character. Employment of various combat arms and special 
troops coordinated by objective, place and time acquired 
decisive importance in achieving success in the battle. Although 
the fire and attack capabilities of infantry units had increased 
significantly by this time in connection with their saturation 
with small-caliber artillery, mortars, medium and light 
machineguns, and flamethrowers, they were incapable of 
successfully penetrating a heavily fortified, deeply echeloned 
enemy defense without the support of artillery and aircraft. 
This was similar to the defense, in which the infantry could not 
independently repel the powerful blow of an attacking enemy, who 
began using a new means of attack in the course of war--tanks. 
  Combat experience introduced much that was new to the system 
of interworking of infantry with artillery. This experience was 
generalized in the work "Artilleriya oborony" [Defense 
Artillery], published in 1917. It stated in particular: 
"Artillery work saves infantry blood and reduces shell 
consumption. . . . It will be people who will compile and 
implement the artillery defense plan. If they do not believe in 
the possibility of using the full power of modern artillery, if 
they do not personally visit all hills, valleys and 
emplacements, if they do not study the terrain and enemy in 
detail, if they break away from the commanders of regiments and 
infantry, and if they talk with artillerymen of neighboring 
divisions and issue missions to battery commanders not on the 
terrain, but over the telephone and from a map, then the 
artillery plan will resemble a house built on sand, and 
artillery sweat that is saved will be paid for by infantry 
blood."[.sup]7[/] 
  In the offensive, artillery assisted in the infantry's 
forward movement to take up a line of departure for the attack; 
it breached barbed-wire entanglements; it demolished defensive 
works, machinegun nests, observation posts, shelters, 
emplacements and connecting passages in breakthrough sectors; it 
fought enemy artillery; and it supported the infantry assault 
and prevented enemy counterattacks. In the defense it would 
inflict losses on the enemy in repelling his assaults, support 
flanks and boundaries and the conduct of counterattacks, and 
execute a maneuver of fire to destroy a wedged-in enemy. 
  Rejected at the beginning of the war in the majority of 
armies, artillery preparation of the attack was legitimized once 
and for all in the course of the war.[.sup]8[/] In executing 
it, the artillery was employed centrally in three groups: 1) 
group for breaching barbed-wire entanglements; 2) group for 
demolishing fortifications and neutralizing the defensive fire 
plan; 3) group for combating enemy artillery. What was new in 
the interworking of infantry with artillery was that following 
artillery preparation of the attack a portion of the light 
batteries would be resubordinated to commanders of infantry 
regiments and would proceed behind the infantry to support it 
during battle in the depth of the defense.[.sup]9[/] 
  Artillery support of an infantry assault was accomplished by 
a creeping barrage, but its depth was not great. The absence of 
regimental and battalion artillery had a negative effect on 
assurance of independence of infantry subunit operations. What 
was new in organizing interworking during the fight against 
enemy artillery was that firing was conducted with the help of 
spotter aircraft, tethered balloons, and in some cases 
sound-ranging stations. 
  The first experience of infantry and artillery interworking 
with tanks and aircraft was received in the course of World War 
I. Combat employment of tanks showed that they were an effective 
means of penetrating fortified enemy positions despite their 
technical imperfection. While 32 tanks took part in the 
operation on the Somme, there already were 378 (battle tanks) in 
the operation at Cambrai and 511 at Amiens.[.sup]10[/] Rates 
of advance increased with the commitment of tanks; the tanks 
were attached to the infantry. The infantry's tactics changed, 
and it began to employ new methods of battle--shifting to a 
group combat formation and group tactics. 
  Aircraft saw much development during the war. Aviation 
initially was considered a means of supporting the 
infantry-artillery battle and it performed reconnaissance and 
spotted artillery fire. But its functions expanded with the 
appearance of ground attack, fighter and bomber aviation. By the 
end of the war aircraft were fighting for air superiority in the 
course of operations. One thousand or more aircraft took part in 
the largest ones. Tactical air defense tactics developed in the 
battle against aircraft and an air defense service was 
established. The method of firing on flying aircraft from 
machineguns and rifles saw some improvement. 
  With the predominance of positional forms of warfare, the 
cavalry faded more and more into the background as a combat arm, 
although there were examples of its major, bold 
operations.[.sup]11[/] During a breakthrough of the enemy 
defense the cavalry would dismount and be employed as infantry. 
Employing cavalry to exploit progress in an operation was 
unsuccessful, with certain exceptions. This was explained by the 
fact that the cavalry was poorly equipped with machineguns and 
artillery and could not surmount the infantry's increased fire 
resistance. 
  The role of engineer troops increased steadily during the 
war. Evidence of this was the circumstance that their proportion 
in the makeup of ground troops had increased by 1.5-2 times by 
the end of the war.[.sup]12[/] They performed various 
engineer support missions in battle. Interworking of engineer 
subunits with infantry and artillery was substantially enriched. 
Combat engineer teams would perform engineer reconnaissance in 
their support. By day such reconnaissance would be conducted by 
observation and by night sometimes by a probing reconnaissance 
patrol. The reconnaissance mission included collecting 
information about the general nature of positions; arrangement 
of emplacements, connecting passages and shelters; nature of 
barriers and obstacles; locations of machineguns and mortars; 
locations of fougasses; and degree of terrain passability in 
front of the enemy defense frontage. 
  To support the infantry's advance in an offensive, a first 
echelon regiment usually received two combat engineer platoons 
as attachment and the division received one company of a 
military road construction detachment. Special attention was 
given to breaching obstacles during an assault and during battle 
in the depth of the defense. Lanes were cleared chiefly by the 
explosive method by specially formed "demolition teams" (two 
teams for each lead assaulting company). Wire cutters, grappling 
hooks and grenades would be used for breaching during battle in 
the depth of the enemy defense. 
  In the defense, engineer units and subunits would be used 
primarily for building obstacles (barbed-wire entanglements and 
minefields). The obstacles would be deeply echeloned and several 
belts of wire entanglement netting would be prepared. The 
Russian Army used powder obstacles (fougasses) as explosive 
fougasses. They were divided into field, fortress and river 
obstacles and by technical characteristics into conventional, 
contact-detonation and repeating fougasses. They usually were 
used in barbed-wire entanglements, especially to cover dead 
zones. Fougasses were set up in two or three lines in groups of 
5-15 charges at a distance of 8-12 m from each other; the 
distance between lines was 20-30 m.[.sup]13[/] 
  Duties of unit and formation commanders in organizing 
interworking became more complicated in the course of 
development of combined arms battle in World War I. At the 
beginning of the war regimental commanders were its main 
organizers. They would assign missions to the infantry and 
artillery and coordinate their combat efforts. The role of 
division commanders was limited to assigning general missions to 
regiments, giving their commanders full initiative in organizing 
and controlling battle. With transition to positional forms of 
war, with the increased depth of combat formations and with 
development of technical means of warfare, interworking began to 
be organized according to the principle of rigid 
centralization--division commanders would delve into all details 
of battle and coordinate combat efforts among units and subunits 
of combat arms and with adjacent units. 
  The nature of interworking of Red Army troops in the Civil 
War was distinguished by great uniqueness dictated by the 
specifics of combat operations. So-called "rail war" tactics 
were used in the summer of 1918. Battles were fought primarily 
along main rail lines.[.sup]14[/] Operations of dismounted 
units and subunits were supported by guns set up on flatcars. 
  Interworking of infantry and artillery became more 
complicated with an expansion of the frontage of combat 
operations. Many divisions and brigades were forced to operate 
with a significant separation from the main body. Under these 
conditions interworking was organized in the most general terms. 
For example, in organizing for battle near Izhevsk in the fall 
of 1918, V. M. Azin, commander of the 2nd (subsequently the 
28th) Composite Division, gave subordinate commanders only a 
general mission and the final objective of operations. "You 
cannot count on my support," he said. 
  As experience was gained, combat efforts were coordinated in 
greater detail. Combat missions would be assigned to divisions 
by axes and objectives. The populated points which had to be 
taken usually were indicated to brigades (regiments). The attack 
was accomplished by march columns which, on reaching the enemy 
artillery effect zone (4-6 km), would deploy into company and 
platoon columns and then into an extended line. The assault 
would be made after a brief fire assault. For closer 
interworking with infantry, the artillery would be distributed 
by battalion among rifle regiments and brigades. Without 
becoming an organizational part of these units, the batteries or 
battalions would be assigned to them as it were and constantly 
operate with them, being directly in combat formations of the 
infantry or cavalry. 
  With consideration of situation conditions, in a number of 
cases special artillery groups which usually combined from four 
to six batteries would be established for combating enemy 
artillery. The batteries included in their makeup would be 
shifted to support rifle units after performing assigned 
missions. In this connection, decentralized control exercised 
within the framework of the battery or battalion predominated. 
Brigade and regimental commanders would decide all questions of 
interworking with their commanders. In the course of battle 
special attention would be given to coordinating operations of 
infantry with artillery, which would accompany the attackers by 
fire and wheels. The infantry in turn would cover the artillery 
against enemy cavalry assaults. 
  Rifle units would interwork with cavalry chiefly when it was 
committed to a breakthrough for pursuit of the enemy and in 
making close and deep envelopments. Operating in the enemy rear, 
the cavalry often would spread panic in his ranks, and thereby 
support the infantry's success. 
  Divisions would be reinforced by armored trains and one or 
two armored detachments on the most important axes. In 
organizing interworking with them, commanders would specify 
methods of supporting the infantry by the fire of armored trains 
and would coordinate operations of rifle units with armored 
detachments in taking populated points. Signals for denoting the 
infantry's position would be specified in organizing 
interworking with aviation. Aircraft would bomb from low 
altitudes in support of rifle units. 
  Some success in interworking of combat arms was received in 
conducting defensive battle in the Civil War. Special attention 
was given to establishing a perimeter defense around populated 
points and road junctions. Batteries and battalions would be 
attached to brigades and regiments to ensure independence of 
their operations. Coordination of efforts with artillery was 
achieved by joint disposition of observation posts and by 
setting up a unified range card and a general target and firing 
chart. Some experience was received in fighting enemy tanks. An 
artillery antitank defense system was established for the first 
time in the history of military art in 51st Rifle Division in 
the Kakhovka base of operations in 1920. 
  Special pieces were assigned to combat tanks (armored 
targets) and were not supposed to be diverted to perform other 
missions. Each antitank gun was covered by barrage fire of at 
least one light battery. Mobile batteries and platoons which 
played the role of a unique antitank reserve were used widely to 
build up the density of antitank fire. This defense proved 
insurmountable for the tanks and armored vehicles of Vrangel's 
troops. 
  Combat engineer units interworked closely with infantry and 
artillery. In a period of defensive battles they would help the 
infantry prepare defensive lines, set up obstacles, blow up 
bridges on routes of enemy advance, and demolish individual 
railroad sections. Demolition teams would be set up to perform 
demolition work. In offensive battle combat engineers would 
perform engineer reconnaissance of terrain, restore bridges, and 
build crossings over water obstacles. For example, V. I. 
Chapayev, commander of the 25th Rifle Division, assigned combat 
engineer subunits the following missions in an assault crossing 
of the Belaya River south of Ufa in June 1918: Perform engineer 
reconnaissance of the river in the crossing sector; repair the 
damaged ferry for crossing armored vehicles; build landings 
(docks) on both banks of the river; and repair the road from the 
armored vehicle unloading site to the ferry 
crossing.[.sup]15[/] 
  The experience of interworking accumulated by the Red Army 
in 
the Civil War was reflected in regulation documents published at 
that time--the "Stroyevoy pekhotnyy ustav RKKA" [Workers' and 
Peasants' Red Army Infantry Drill Regulations] (1920), "Ustav 
artillerii RKKA" [RKKA Artillery Regulations] (1920), "Ustav 
rotnykh pulemetov RKKA" [RKKA Light Machinegun Regulations] 
(1920) and also in the work "Boyevoye primeneniye strelkovoy 
divizii i vysshikh kavaleriyskikh soyedineniy" [Combat 
Employment of Rifle Divisions and the Highest Cavalry 
Formations] (1920). 
  There was no pause in the arms race following the end of 
World War I. To the contrary, it was conducted at 
unprecedentedly high rates. In relatively short time periods the 
technical outfitting of armies of the leading world countries 
was upgraded and replaced almost completely. Of ground troops' 
armament, one should note above all the rapidly improving 
armored equipment. In the late 1930's and early 1940's medium 
and heavy tanks appeared with improved hull shape and armor, a 
high speed (45-65 km/hr), a considerable range (up to 500 km), 
powerful armor protection (100 mm or more), and heavy armament 
(from 76-mm to 122-mm guns and heavy-caliber machineguns). 
  Field artillery was improved--guns and howitzers (from 76-mm 
to 203-mm) as well as mortars (from 82-mm to 160-mm), antitank 
artillery (from 45-mm to 100-mm), antitank guns, and 
antiaircraft artillery (from 37-mm to 85-mm). New machineguns 
and submachineguns (assault rifles) were adopted. Antitank and 
antipersonnel mines became widespread. Tank, mechanized, 
airborne and artillery divisions and corps as well as other 
units appeared in the makeup of the ground troops. Aviation 
developed intensively, especially during World War II. New 
fighters, ground attack aircraft, medium and long-range 
(strategic) bombers, long-range reconnaissance aircraft, 
military-transport aircraft and gliders appeared. 
  The theory and practice of interworking by Soviet troops 
were 
upgraded in the interwar period with consideration of the 
qualitative renewal of the material base of combined arms 
battle. This process did not occur without contradictions. On 
the one hand, based on prevision of the nature of future war, 
Soviet military thinking developed a scientifically grounded 
concept of balanced Armed Forces development. In contrast to 
one-sided foreign military theories of "air war" and "tank war," 
which overestimated the role of individual combat arms in 
performing missions in the operation and battle, our military 
art firmly adhered to the idea of coordinated, massive 
employment of branches of the Armed Forces and combat arms to 
rout the enemy and achieve the assigned objectives. On the other 
hand, adherence to Civil War experience dominated and proper 
priorities in development of weapons were not always chosen. 
  Questions of interworking were set forth for the first time 
in the most generalized form in the 1925 Field Service 
Regulations, which emphasized that coordination in operations of 
combat arms and various units and detachments operating on 
different axes is a necessary condition for success. Inasmuch as 
the Red Army had few tanks and aircraft at that time, the 
Regulations gave no consideration to their support. Artillery 
was regarded as the basic means for fire suppression of the 
enemy. According to the Regulations, in penetrating an organized 
enemy defense it was deemed necessary to have a treble 
superiority over the enemy in personnel and equipment. 
  Subsequently the system of interworking was developed and 
significantly supplemented and updated in the 1929 Field Service 
Regulations, the 1936 RKKA Provisional Field Service 
Regulations, and the 1939, 1940 and 1941 draft Red Army Field 
Service Regulations. These regulations examined questions of 
organizing interworking not only in rifle, but also in 
mechanized, cavalry and motorized formations. 
  In addition to regulation documents, much influence on 
improving the theory and practice of interworking was exerted by 
works of M. N. Tukhachevskiy "Novoye v razvitii taktiki Krasnoy 
Armii" [New Things in Development of Red Army Tactics], V. K. 
Triandafillov "Kharakter operatsiy sovremennykh armiy" [Nature 
of Operations of Modern Armies], G. S. Isserson "Istoricheskiye 
korni glubokoy taktiki" [Historical Roots of Deep Tactics], the 
collective work of the Frunze Military Academy "Organizatsiya i 
vedeniye nastupatelnogo boya" [Organization and Conduct of 
Offensive Battle], S. K. Timoshenko "O takticheskoy podgotovke 
voysk" [On Tactical Training of Troops], A. G. Lignau 
"Vzaimodeystviye ognya i zhivoy sily v nastupatelnom boyu" 
[Interworking of Fire and Personnel in Offensive Battle], A. I. 
Sedyakin "Blizhniy boy" [Close Combat], S. M. Budennyy 
"Znacheniye konnitsy i osnovy yeye taktiki" [Importance of 
Cavalry and Fundamentals of Its Tactics], the collective work 
edited by V. D. Grendal "Artilleriya v nastupatelnom boyu" 
[Artillery in Offensive Battle], K. B. Kalinovskiy "Tanki v 
gruppakh DD" [Tanks in Long Range Groups], A. P. Lapchinskiy 
"Vozdushnyy boy" [Air-to-Air Combat], and D. M. Karbyshev 
"Inzhenernoye obespecheniye obshchevoyskovogo boya" [Engineer 
Support to Combined arms Battle]. 
  Many questions of theory and practice of troop interworking 
in that period were resolved by Soviet military thought in a 
fundamentally new way based on the theory of deep battle set 
forth in the instructions "Vremennyye ukazaniya po organizatsii 
glubokogo boya" [Provisional Directions on Organizing Deep 
Battle] (1933). Subsequently, it was also based on the theory of 
the deep operation. Briefly, the essence of the system of 
interworking in accomplishing a deep operation reduced to the 
following. Rifle formations reinforced by tanks and supported by 
artillery and aircraft make a break-in of a positional enemy 
defensive front; when the front is disrupted, motorized and 
mechanized units (mechanized corps and brigades) are committed, 
they advance swiftly into the depth of the enemy defense 
together with airborne assault forces, rout army reserves and 
take tactically important objectives (rear-area logistic support 
bases, airfields, transportation hubs). Cavalry supported by 
aircraft attacks shallower reserves, seizes light aviation 
airfields, and destroys retreating enemy rear 
services.[.sup]16[/] 
  But it is impossible to be silent about the fact that not 
all 
questions of interworking were resolved correctly in our 
regulation documents and works. Thus, for a long time the 
cavalry was advanced to the fore to the detriment of development 
of armored troops. The role of infantry in combined arms battle 
was also exaggerated. The textbook "Obshchaya taktika" [General 
Tactics], published on the eve of the war,[.sup]17[/] stated: 
"All interworking is organized in support of infantry (which 
performs the principal role in battle)." Dividing the combat 
formation of formations and units in the offensive into striking 
forces and holding forces proved impractical. 
  Many miscalculations were made in organizing the 
interworking 
of artillery with infantry. It was envisaged to establish 
artillery groups for a specific purpose. For example, 
infantry-support artillery groups were established in the 
division based on the number of rifle regiments operating in the 
first echelon, and long-range artillery groups were established 
in corps based on the number of first echelon divisions. 
Artillery would be subordinated to regimental and battalion 
commanders only "when, based on ground observation conditions, 
it becomes difficult to support an offensive by centrally 
controlled fire."[.sup]18[/] As shown by Great Patriotic War 
experience, rigid centralization in controlling artillery led to 
where regiments and battalions essentially ended up without 
artillery support in the course of a battle. 
  The established procedure for initiating the assault did not 
facilitate precise interworking between infantry and artillery. 
The 1936 "Vremennyy polevoy ustav RKKA" [Workers' and Peasants' 
Red Army Provisional Field Service Regulations] directed that 
the infantry should make an assault dash when the artillery 
transfers fire into the depth of the defense. In practice this 
led during the war to where a gap in time was created between 
fire and the movement of infantry. Taking advantage of this, the 
enemy often managed to poise to repel an assault. Subsequently 
this provision was corrected based on combat experience. 
  Questions of interworking in defensive battle were not 
developed completely enough in prewar times. The Field Service 
Regulations gave no consideration to coordinated operations of 
troops in repelling a surprise enemy attack, to the procedure 
for restoring combat effectiveness, or to questions of 
interworking when destroying enemy groupings wedged in at 
boundaries and on flanks, when they made close and deep 
envelopments, during a withdrawal, and in fighting in 
encirclement. 
  The fact that regulation documents underestimated the 
combined arms commander's role in organizing interworking was an 
especially big mistake. Thus, the 1935 "Nastavleniye po polevoy 
sluzhbe shtabov" [Manual of Staff Field Duties] pointed out that 
the chief of staff personally organizes and ensures interworking 
of troops. It was recommended that the commander give only 
general instructions for organizing interworking. All these and 
many other miscalculations in questions of interworking had a 
negative effect on the course of Soviet troop combat operations 
in the first period of war. 
  The process of improving the system of interworking when 
Soviet troops conducted combat operations in the 
Great Patriotic War followed difficult paths. An analysis of our 
failures with the beginning of the war shows that most often 
they resulted from poor preparation for combat and the absence 
of reliable interworking among the combat arms involved. Only in 
1941 did the Headquarters, Supreme High Command [Hq SHC] issue 
several directives on this matter. Thus, one published in August 
noted that combined arms commanders and staffs were doing 
extremely poorly in coordinating the actions of infantry and 
artillery with tanks and combat engineers. Interworking was 
being organized in general outlines not on the terrain, but from 
a map; it was being worked out to a shallow depth without 
considering troop combat capabilities; missions were being 
assigned in an ill-conceived manner; and combat efforts of units 
and subunits were being poorly coordinated for destroying an 
enemy wedged in at boundaries and flanks.[.sup]19[/] 
  The directives indicated that the principal reason for the 
inability of many combined arms commanders to organize 
interworking was that they had a poor knowledge of combat 
capabilities of the combat arms. Not knowing how the combat arms 
should be employed in battle, they naturally could not demand 
that subordinate commanders employ them properly.[.sup]20[/] 
  A genuine scourge for troops in the first period of war was 
the knowingly unrealistic assignment of missions to divisions, 
regiments and battalions. Thus, in a directive to troops during 
the battles at Smolensk (1941), 19th Army Chief of Staff Major 
General P. N. Rubtsov instructed: "...Trouble continues to occur 
in calculating time and space. The desire to execute an assigned 
combat mission as quickly as possible often obscures common 
sense, and troops are assigned missions of which they clearly 
are incapable."[.sup]21[/] 
  It is typical that the command element's instructions not 
only noted shortcomings that occurred in organization of 
interworking, but also spelled out specific ways of remedying 
them. For example, a 29 September 1941 Hq SHC directive pointed 
out: "In organizing interworking, commanders must know precisely 
the force composition and missions of supporting artillery, 
tanks and aviation . . . assign missions to subordinates 
personally on the terrain, and clarify targets for assault, 
suppression and destruction."[.sup]22[/] 
  The 1942 "Boyevoy ustav pekhoty" [Infantry Field Manual] and 
the 1943 draft "Polevoy ustav" [Field Service Regulations] 
played a role of great importance in improving the system of 
interworking in the troops. With consideration of accumulated 
combat experience, they set forth recommendations on how troop 
combat efforts should be coordinated. Thus, the "Polevoy ustav" 
noted that combat missions for the offensive must be assigned in 
such a way that at least 24 hours remain before it begins, 
division or brigade commanders must be given at least 12 hours 
for organizing for battle, and battalion commanders must be 
given at least 3 hours of daylight for work on the terrain. 
  In the third period of the war certain corrections to the 
work of organizing interworking were made based on requirements 
of the "Nastavleniye po proryvu pozitsionnoy oborony" [Manual 
for Breakthrough of a Position Defense]. It prescribed 
allocating a corps commander at least two days, a division 
commander just as much, and regimental and battalion commanders 
at least 24 hours each for organizing interworking. 
Recommendations on developing an operational timetable in the 
division which should detail what mission rifle units, 
artillery, tankers and combat engineers should perform and how 
they should do so in a particular stage of battle were new. 
  Interworking in defensive battle was organized by options of 
conducting the battle, by missions, and by axes of enemy 
operations.[.sup]23[/] For example, in the defense at Moscow 
in November 1941 the commander of 5th Army's 32nd Rifle Division 
coordinated combat efforts for such missions as support to the 
battle of combat outposts, the battle for the FEBA and for 
holding populated points, and battle in the depth of defense. 
  Combat missions were updated subsequently as combat 
experience accumulated. Thus, in the defense at Kursk 
interworking was organized in 15th and 81st guards rifle 
divisions and in 73rd and 213th rifle divisions for the 
following missions: Battle on approaches to the defense and 
prohibition of enemy forward movement into the assault; repulse 
of an enemy assault and the battle to hold the FEBA; the battle 
to destroy a wedged-in enemy; conduct of counterattacks and 
restoration of the defense. 
  And so, a number of trends can be traced in organizing 
interworking in the war years. Its content was significantly 
expanded and enriched. The transition from artillery support to 
artillery offensive became fundamentally new in the interworking 
of artillery with infantry and tanks, and the effectiveness of 
fire damage of the enemy increased as a result. Regulation 
documents pointed out that the essence of the artillery 
offensive "is continuous support to infantry by massed, 
effective artillery and mortar fire throughout the entire period 
of the offensive. Artillery and mortar fire should lead the 
infantry and tanks into the assault from one objective in the 
defense to another."[.sup]24[/] 
  Artillery preparation of the assault usually was planned to 
a 
depth of 3-4 km within a time frame of 1.5-2 hours. What was new 
in planning artillery support was that the mission was executed 
not only by the method of a successive fire concentration, but 
also by a rolling barrage (single or double and sometimes even 
triple), up to a depth of 2 km. 
  During the war, the Soviet command began to see a need for 
reinforcing attacking rifle and tank subunits with close-support 
artillery. Subunits and units of self-propelled artillery 
(SAU-76, SU-122, ISU-152) were established for this and were 
attached to tank subunits as accompanying close-support guns for 
combating enemy antitank and other weapons. The 45-mm and 57-mm 
antitank guns and 76-mm regimental guns, which displaced on the 
battlefield as individual gun crews, were used in rifle 
battalions as accompanying close-support guns. 
  The main air efforts were aimed at winning air superiority, 
reconnoitering the enemy, and assisting combined arms formations 
in defeating him. In the second and third periods of the war, 
Air Force operations were accomplished in the form of an air 
offensive, the basis of which was air preparation of the 
assault, support of an infantry and tank assault, and 
accompaniment of attacking troops in the depth of the enemy 
defense. 
  The landing and operations of airborne assault forces 
represented a fundamentally new phenomenon in World War II (a 
total of 150 major assault landings were made). Airborne assault 
forces would be landed most often in an offensive operation to 
assist the main troop grouping in defeating the enemy. 
Interworking with it was organized on an operational and 
strategic scale. 
  The interworking of tanks with infantry and artillery 
continuously improved during the war. Tank units and subunits 
attached to rifle divisions and regiments would be employed as 
infantry direct-support tanks. Their operations would be planned 
by lines and missions. Directive instructions emphasized that 
tanks should not separate from the infantry by more than 200-400 
m and the infantry should "suppress enemy antitank weapons with 
the full power of their fire as well as by the fire of 
accompanying close-support guns, reconnoiter and clear 
minefields, . . . combat German tank destroyers, decisively 
follow tanks into the assault, consolidate captured lines..." 
Artillery was assigned missions of combating enemy tanks. It was 
emphasized that "tanks fight tanks only in case of a clear 
superiority in forces and when the situation is 
favorable."[.sup]25[/] 
  Interworking of air defense units and subunits with rifle, 
artillery and tank units was accomplished with great difficulty: 
The acute shortage of antiaircraft artillery [AAA] was felt in 
the troops. At the beginning of the war one AAA battalion (8 
37-mm and 4 76-mm AA guns) was envisaged in the makeup of each 
rifle division and corps. A division could establish a density 
of 1.2 guns per kilometer on a frontage of 10 km with organic 
weapons, but even this insufficient density was not always 
established in view of being understrength in weapons. The 
shortage of AAA in the first period of the war forced wide use 
of small arms and passive measures of protection--maskirovka, 
dispersal, use of protective terrain features, engineer 
preparation of terrain--to combat aircraft. 
  Armies began establishing AAA groups beginning with the 
second period of the war. This achieved centralization of 
command and control, massing, and convenience of interworking of 
AAA. The density of AAA cover increased to 10 guns per kilometer 
of frontage or 1-1.5 guns per square kilometer of the area 
covered. In the middle of 1944 some rifle divisions received a 
separate AAA battalion consisting of 12 37-mm guns and an 
antiaircraft company consisting of 18 DShK [Degtyarev-Shpagin 
heavy] machineguns. 
  The experience of organizing the interworking of air defense 
personnel and equipment with other combat arms was reflected in 
the 1944 "Rukovodstvo po boyevomu primeneniyu sredstv PVO pri 
obespechenii voysk" [Manual for Combat Employment of Air Defense 
Weapons in Support of Troops]. It noted that the air defense 
system included the following: Timely enemy air raid warning to 
troops, a VNOS [air observation, warning and communications] 
service, AAA and machinegun fire plan, fighter combat 
operations, and a plan for organized small arms fire. The 
combined arms commander was responsible for organizing air 
defense. 
  In the offensive, air defense weapons concentrated efforts 
on 
covering troops delivering the main attack. Displacing by 
echelon (no more than one-third of batteries simultaneously), 
they were at the following distance from forward units: AA 
machineguns no further than 800-1,000 m, light AAA 1.5-2 km and 
medium AAA 3 km. In covering troops, AAA would proceed in troop 
combat formations in trying to achieve air defense continuity. 
AA machineguns and small-caliber guns always were in readiness 
to fire from the move and from short halts. In the defense, air 
defense weapons had the primary mission of disrupting enemy air 
preparation and not allowing reconnaissance or air strikes 
against artillery positions, reserves, staffs and rear-area 
facilities. 
  During the war abundant experience was gained in 
interworking 
of engineer troops with other combat arms. Operating as part of 
mobile obstacle detachments, assault detachments and teams, and 
movement support detachments or performing independent missions, 
engineer units and subunits would support operations of rifle, 
tank and artillery units and subunits in all kinds of battle. In 
interworking with them, the engineer units and subunits would 
cover flanks, consolidate captured lines, assist troops in 
repelling enemy counterattacks, and support the troops' forward 
movement and maneuver and their establishment of a stable 
defense. Engineer subunits' increased role in battle is 
indicated by the circumstance that in 1945 a rifle division 
began to have up to 12 combat engineer companies. In some 
operations their density rose to 4-6 companies per kilometer of 
frontage.[.sup]26[/] 
  The combined arms commander was the primary organizer of 
interworking in the war. At the same time, the staff played an 
important role in this matter. The 1942 "Nastavleniye po polevoy 
sluzhbe shtabov" [Manual on Staff Field Duties] emphasized that 
a staff which cannot support interworking cannot be deemed a 
full-fledged command and control entity. The staff's duties in 
organizing interworking included the following: Preparing data 
on the combat situation and necessary calculations; coordinating 
questions of interworking with chiefs of combat arms (services) 
and with adjacent units; supporting the commander's work in 
organizing interworking on the terrain, on terrain models or on 
maps; and communicating his instructions to units. In addition, 
the staff would provide uninterrupted communications among 
interworking units and would establish a unified system of 
warning and target designation signals, develop necessary combat 
documentation, and monitor how interworking was organized in 
subordinate units and subunits. 
  An important role in coordinating combat efforts during the 
war was given to tactical drill problems, field-fire exercises, 
command and staff exercises, staff officer radio drills, and 
joint problems for commanders of rifle, tank, artillery and air 
units. In noting the great benefit of such activities at a 
conference critiquing the Silesian Operation, the commander of 
2nd Guards Army noted: "We began holding joint exercises 15-20 
days before the operation began. . . . Subsequently, in the 
period of joint ground reconnaissance, combat arms officers were 
very satisfied and pleasantly surprised by the fact that they 
were training together in problems and would go into battle 
together. They knew each other and developed a certain trust and 
mutual understanding, and this was very valuable for 
battle."[.sup]27[/] 
  On the whole, the Great Patriotic War enriched the theory 
and 
practice of troop interworking and elevated it to a new level. 
Soviet commanders and staffs proved equal to their missions. 
They displayed creative initiative in seeking new, 
nonstereotyped methods of coordinating troop combat efforts 
depending on the situation at hand. As a rule, their activity 
was characterized by depth of concepts, preciseness of 
calculations and comprehensive prudence. 
  Combat experience showed that commanders' proficiency alone 
was not enough to achieve precise, continuous interworking in 
battle. High combat proficiency of privates and NCO's and their 
ability to make effective use of their weapons' combat 
capabilities and act in coordination--conduct fire accurately, 
transfer it promptly to new targets, and carry out mutual 
assistance in battle--also were required. No less important were 
the personnel's high morale and fighting qualities, persistence, 
composure, and an unbending will to win. 
  Qualitative improvement of the material base of combined 
arms 
formations largely helped upgrade the system of interworking of 
Soviet troops. Thus, during 1943-1944, for example, the 
numerical strength of personnel of the army in the field rose by 
a little more than 6 percent, but the number of guns and mortars 
which they had rose by 40 percent, the number of tanks and 
self-propelled artillery by 90 percent, and the number of 
aircraft almost fourfold.[.sup]28[/] It is typical that the 
proportion of the numerical strength of different combat arms in 
the rifle division by the end of the war increased to 50-60 
percent, while it did not exceed 20 percent in infantry 
divisions in World War I. 
  According to the "Troop Leadership" manual, interworking in 
the fascist German Army was considered one of the 
chief tactical principles. Military command element orders 
emphasized that personnel, equipment or time should not be 
spared to achieve uniformity, precision, coordination of 
operations and punctuality in executing missions. From 12 hours 
to 2 days were allocated for coordinating questions of 
interworking in the division in preparing an 
offensive.[.sup]29[/] Principal attention in the offensive 
was given to close interworking of infantry, tanks, artillery 
and aircraft. Tanks would clear the way for motorized infantry, 
which would consolidate success. The tank and motorized reserve 
intended for exploiting success and accomplishing sudden 
missions that arose would move behind the motorized infantry in 
a wedge combat formation. 
  During the war many corrections were made to the system of 
interworking of combined arms units by the fascist German 
troops' military command. An assault most often was executed 
simultaneously by tanks and motorized infantry with continuous 
accompaniment by aircraft. After artillery preparation of the 
assault, artillery and mortars would switch to artillery support 
of the assault, which was executed by a successive fire 
concentration or rolling barrage. Target designation and mutual 
coordination of infantry and tank operations with artillery and 
aircraft were distinguished by great precision. 
  In the defense, the combat efforts of combat arms were aimed 
at routing the enemy ahead of the forward edge of the "main 
battlefield" or at the very least inside the main defensive 
zone. To this end, in coordination with aircraft, artillery 
would prepare long-range fires on road junctions, chokepoints, 
and crossings. The most dangerous axes, boundaries and flanks 
would be covered by a fixed barrage. The infantry would 
establish a zone of massed, continuous rifle and machinegun fire 
ahead of the FEBA. Tanks and self-propelled artillery would be 
employed as fixed weapon emplacements and roving guns. 
  Questions of interworking were developed only in a general 
way in prewar U.S. Army field manuals. It is 
characteristic that tanks were not singled out as an independent 
combat arm. Their operations were covered in the "Infantry" 
sections. The Air Force, to the contrary, was separated out. It 
trained for independent operations. Tactical interworking of 
aircraft with ground troops on the battlefield was 
underestimated. The Americans paid for these and other 
miscalculations with losses in the first battles. 
  During the war commanders and staffs gave great attention to 
coordinating combat efforts of the combat arms. In organizing a 
breakthrough of the enemy defense, special attention was given 
to its reliable fire suppression in support of infantry and tank 
operations. To this end, a large number of aircraft were used 
for fire preparation of the assault in addition to artillery. 
Thus, 300-400 and sometimes even up to 500 tons of bombs per 
square kilometer were allocated to support an army corps 
offensive. 
  British Army wartime field manuals reflected the 
principle of interworking rather completely, but it was not 
always skillfully realized in practice. Offensive operations in 
the El Alamein area (1942) can serve as an example. Despite the 
fact that the British surpassed Italian-German troops by 1.5 
times in personnel, by 2 times in tanks and artillery and by 
several times in aircraft, the offensive was carried out at a 
low rate because of poor coordination of tank and infantry 
efforts with artillery and also inflexible command and control. 
In particular, aircraft were not used effectively. Bombing was 
not against targets, but areas. Air strikes did not conclude 
with an assault by ground troops. Artillery fire also was 
conducted against areas. And when guns and mortars fell silent 
and aircraft stopped flying sorties, the infantry and tanks, 
left without fire support, would launch an assault and suffer 
losses from enemy fire. 
  Interworking of British troops was accomplished rather 
precisely in subsequent operations. Operations of infantry, 
tanks and artillery were tied in skillfully with aircraft in 
accomplishing "close air support," which corresponded to our 
concept of the "air offensive." 
  Japanese Army tactics were characterized by great 
independence of operations by lightly armed detachments, 
especially in jungles and on mountainous terrain. The full 
burden of battle fell on the infantry. Artillery would conduct 
fire against areas; moreover, there was little artillery. The 
shortage of artillery was made up for by air operations; tanks 
were not employed everywhere. For example, tank troops did not 
see wide employment in combat operations in the southern seas. 
Only light tanks and light field artillery were used in battles. 
  In a defensive battle the Japanese relied chiefly on the 
staunchness of their infantry. The strong side of their defense 
was the troops' ability to adapt to terrain, make wide use of 
obstacles and ambushes, and make daring sallies into the enemy 
rear. Special raiding parties were established to destroy 
artillery batteries. Deceptive actions often were used in the 
defense, and fire would be opened from short range. Surprise 
counterattacks were widely employed, especially at night. On the 
whole, the defense was distinguished by great tenacity. In many 
cases defensive positions were defended to the last soldier. 
  The system of interworking saw some development in 
local wars. The employment of new kinds of weapons 
(jet aviation, combat helicopters, antitank and surface-to-air 
missile systems, new types of artillery, tanks, IFV's, homing 
munitions, fuel-air bombs and so on) dictated the appearance of 
new methods for coordinating combat efforts of personnel and 
equipment. For example, the complexity of interworking of ground 
troops with aviation increased sharply. Flights at supersonic 
speed hampered delivery of strikes against small targets near 
friendly troops due to brief time over the target and the 
difficulty of identifying it. 
  In connection with the conduct of airmobile operations, the 
need arose to organize interworking among motorized infantry, 
tanks, artillery and the combat and transport-attack helicopters 
which landed airborne assault forces and provided fire support. 
  The importance of the time factor rose substantially in 
coordinating combat efforts under the new conditions. Staff use 
of automated control systems simplified the solution to some 
planning questions, and especially facilitated performance of 
complex operational-tactical calculations. Based on an analysis 
of the Vietnam War experience, American specialists concluded 
that the time for planning combat operations for certain 
missions is reduced from 10 hours to 10 minutes using automated 
control systems.[.sup]30[/] 
  It can be seen from the above that the system of troop 
interworking underwent a complicated evolution over many 
centuries of the development of military art. Much accumulated 
experience remains significant even now. But weapons are 
changing and troop interworking changes; therefore past 
experience can be viewed only as a small step in ascending to 
new levels of combat perfection. 
<H5>  2. Principle of Interworking in Defensive Battle </H5>
  Experience in organizing and accomplishing interworking 
gained by Soviet troops in the Great Patriotic War served as the 
foundation, the starting point, for upgrading its system under 
present conditions. The principle of interworking is especially 
sensitive to changes in the material base of combined arms 
battle. Outfitting troops with new weapons and increasing their 
fire, striking, maneuver and protective qualities demand new 
approaches to realizing this and other principles in battle. 
  This section sets the goal of tracing how the content of 
interworking and conditions for its organization in modern 
defensive battle are changing and what new factors are 
influencing work methods of commanders and staffs, and on this 
basis developing certain practical recommendations for command 
and control entities in coordinating troop combat efforts. 
  The system of troop interworking presently functioning and 
reflected in field manuals is the result of lengthy historical 
development. Many provisions on interworking in prewar Red Army 
Field Service Regulations were viewed completely differently 
than now. For example, it was believed that combat efforts of 
combat arms and elements of the combat formation should be 
coordinated by lines and objectives in the 
defense.[.sup]31[/] But that procedure of interworking was 
refuted by combat experience during the Great Patriotic War. 
This happened because "lines and objectives" are a very vague, 
nonspecific concept. It often turned out that each of the 
interworking commanders would designate them at his own 
discretion, which did not contribute to achieving uniformity of 
understanding of the objective of operations in battle, and this 
is the primary task in organizing interworking. Therefore it was 
determined in the course of the war that it was more advisable 
to organize interworking in the defense not by lines, but by 
missions being performed by troops.[.sup]32[/] This permitted 
tying in troop operations more purposefully in conducting 
battle. Subsequently, in addition to coordinating efforts by 
missions, it also was deemed necessary to organize interworking 
by options of defensive battle and by axes of enemy operations. 
  In principle, with some updating, this system of organizing 
interworking in the defense also is deemed advisable for present 
conditions. Thus, the "Boyevoy ustav Sukhoputnykh voysk" [Ground 
Troops Field Manual] presently in force states: "The battalion 
(company) commander organizes interworking by missions, probable 
axes of enemy advance, and options of subunit 
operations."[.sup]33[/] 
  But while the logical schematic for coordinating troop 
combat 
efforts in the modern defense basically remains the same, the 
content of interworking and work methods of commanders and 
staffs in organizing it are changing substantially. Much has 
appeared here that is new. The expansion in spatial limits of 
battle has a great influence on the system of interworking. 
Thus, in determining the probable nature of enemy operations, it 
is now no longer possible, as in the past, to be limited to 
considering only that enemy grouping directly facing a formation 
or unit. 
  Proper coordination of defending troops' combat efforts 
requires anticipating what personnel and equipment the attacker 
can commit in conducting not only close combat, but also 
long-range battle. It is a question above all of means of 
nuclear attack, reconnaissance-strike and reconnaissance-fire 
complexes, and remote minelaying and EW equipment, the bulk of 
which is at the disposal of formation commanders and is 
dispersed at a considerable distance from the front line and in 
a broad zone. 
  The circumstance that modern battle has assumed a land-air 
nature also substantially affects the character of interworking. 
While in the World War II period a division commander preparing 
calculation data for coordinating troop combat efforts chiefly 
estimated the opposing enemy ground grouping and would estimate 
the air situation only in general, now, when combat operations 
on land and in the air comprise a single whole and are waged 
with identically high combat intensity, in coordinating troop 
combat efforts it is important to consider enemy use of tactical 
aviation, whose scale of employment is becoming ever broader, as 
shown by the experience of NATO troop exercises and Operation 
Desert Storm. Thus, a U.S. division is assigned 120-140 sorties 
for a day of battle.[.sup]34[/] 
  The landing of airborne assault forces is becoming massive. 
The U.S. command views them as an important element in realizing 
the "deep strike" concept. Based on NATO troop exercise 
experience, tactical airborne landings are made to a depth of 
60-70 km at brigade strength from the army corps, to 15-20 km at 
battalion strength from the division, and to 5-7 km at company 
strength from the brigade. In addition, wide use of raiding and 
reconnaissance units is envisaged. For example, up to 60 such 
teams are assigned from each Ranger battalion, 24 raiding and 
reconnaissance detachments from the army corps deep 
reconnaissance company, and 50-100 such detachments from a 
special-purpose team.[.sup]35[/] 
  Under those conditions the system for interworking of 
defending troops must be especially flexible. In coordinating 
combat operations, the division commander must take into account 
that aggressive combat operations can take in the full depth of 
the tactical defense zone simultaneously from the very beginning 
of battle. Based on this, it is necessary to provide for the 
possibility of units and subunits performing diverse sudden 
missions that arise and to tie in operations of all combat 
formation elements in such a way that they can repel enemy 
strikes not only from the front, but also from the flanks and 
rear, fight in encirclement, and combine positional and mobile 
forms of warfare. 
  Increased complexity of the mine situation has no small 
influence on interworking of troops in modern battle. It is 
common knowledge that the concept of "mine warfare" was 
officially incorporated in U.S. Army regulations in the 
mid-1980's. The most important role in it was set aside for use 
of remote minelaying systems and remotely laid minefields. Thus, 
according to U.S. command views, remotely laid minefields will 
make up 80 percent of the total volume of obstacles emplaced in 
an air-land offensive operation.[.sup]36[/] 
  In coordinating troop operations it is important to take 
into 
account when, in what stage of battle, for what purpose, against 
what area and by what method the attacking enemy may employ 
remote minelaying systems and accordingly think out questions of 
how to organize observation and a mine danger warning to troops, 
how to reconnoiter remotely laid minefields, how to clear lanes 
in them, and also what the procedure is for restoring unit and 
subunit combat effectiveness after the enemy delivers a massive 
fire strike by remote minelaying systems. 
  Tactical exercise experience shows that in connection with 
the expanded spatial scope of modern battle, the combined arms 
formation commander must have data on the enemy grouping 
disposed on a territory 2-3 times larger than the division area 
of responsibility for a full situation estimate in support of 
decisionmaking and organization of interworking. In short, now 
he is obligated to keep an eye on the enemy continuously not 
only at the tactical but also at the operational level. It 
stands to reason that data of the situation taking shape in 
zones of adjacent units must be communicated to the commander by 
the adjacent units and by higher headquarters. 
  The end result of the enemy estimate in support of 
organization of interworking should be an identification of axes 
of his delivery of the main attack and other attacks, 
identification of the makeup and nature of operations by 
groupings on each axis, and possible methods of his delivery of 
fire strikes and execution of a maneuver of personnel and 
equipment on the ground and by air. 
  The interests of interworking in modern defensive battle 
demand that forecasting of the nature of friendly troop 
operations be more comprehensive and on a larger scale. This is 
connected with the fact that tactics depends on operational art 
and strategy now as never before. The division is capable of 
accomplishing many combat missions only in close interworking 
with operational-level assets which combat enemy aviation, 
reconnaissance-strike complexes, cruise missiles, robotized 
weapons and EW assets; disrupt his system for command and 
control of troops and weapons; provide reliable air and 
antilanding defense and so on. 
  Consequently, in making the decision for battle and in 
organizing interworking, the division commander should have a 
clear picture of the role and place of his formation in the 
operation and its capabilities to perform the assigned combat 
mission, and know how interworking is organized with the senior 
commander's personnel and equipment and with adjacent units, 
especially in such matters as disrupting or weakening an enemy 
precision weapons strike; combating his aircraft, 
reconnaissance, airborne assault forces and EW assets; 
conducting counterpreparation fire; prohibiting the forward 
movement of attack groupings from forming-up places to the final 
coordination line; and also providing protection of friendly 
command and control systems and electronics against enemy 
jamming. 
  In analyzing conditions affecting the organization of 
interworking in modern defensive battle, it is important to note 
the increased volume and complexity of tasks being performed in 
coordinating combat efforts and at the same time the sharp 
reduction in time set aside for carrying them out. While 3-4 
days most often were allocated in the Great Patriotic War for 
organizing interworking at the division-regimental level in 
preparing a defense in the absence of immediate contact with the 
enemy, now a matter of hours will be set aside for this purpose, 
especially in the initial period of war. 
  It is necessary to call attention to the fact that in making 
decisions and organizing interworking, the commander and staff 
now must collect, generalize and process approximately 4-5 times 
more information than in the past war. Information has become 
more complex in content, and collecting and evaluating it 
require greater efforts. This is dictated by the fact that the 
combat operations zone of formations and units has increased by 
many times. For example, while a division in the Great Patriotic 
War defended a zone 10-12 km wide and 6-8 km deep and the area 
of its "combat zone" was 60-100 km[.sup]2[/], a division now 
receives a defensive area 30-40 km or more wide and 20-30 km 
deep based on NATO troop exercise experience.[.sup]37[/] 
Accordingly, the territory on which formation defensive 
operations unfold increased to 600-1,200 km[.sup]2[/], which 
exceeds the division "combat zone" in the past war by 10-12 
times. 
  With consideration of the increased number of missions for 
collecting, processing and analyzing information and performing 
operational-tactical calculations in order to organize 
interworking, a decisive role belongs to simulation of combat 
operations and to skilled, creative use of computers by 
officials of command and control entities. Above all, performing 
calculation and information tasks using computers involves 
assessing combat capabilities of units and subunits, the 
quantitative and qualitative ratio of the sides' personnel and 
equipment by axes and by successively performed missions, and 
personnel and equipment densities being established; assessing 
the effectiveness of enemy nuclear and fire damage; establishing 
a fire plan; determining methods of combat employment of field 
artillery, air defense weapons and army aviation; assessing 
capabilities of tactical reconnaissance and EW; and organizing 
engineer and logistic support. 
  In organizing interworking it must be taken into account 
that 
defensive battle usually begins with a repulse of a massive 
enemy air strike, which can immediately encompass all elements 
of the troop combat alignment. The attacker obviously will 
concentrate his main efforts on destroying weapons; facilities 
for command and control of troops and weapons; targets of the 
antitank defense, air defense and antilanding defense systems; 
as well as troops defending in main and second defense zones and 
reserves. Taking this into account, top-priority measures in 
coordinating troop combat operations are aimed at creating 
favorable conditions for delivering a massive surprise 
retaliatory fire strike against the enemy and preserving 
stability of the defense, no matter what. 
  Based on tactical exercise experience, in organizing 
interworking in this stage special attention is given to 
ensuring troop survivability by a sensible alignment of the 
combat formation of units and subunits, their optimum dispersal, 
timely development of a set of protective measures, prompt 
removal of troops away from presumed massive enemy strikes, and 
execution of a decisive fire-evasion maneuver. To this end the 
combined arms commander determines probable axes of enemy air 
raids, lines from which fire support helicopter attacks are 
possible, and favorable locations for air defense weapon firing 
positions to repel surprise enemy air operations. 
  We will note that tactics of conducting combat operations by 
the roving ambush method have seen wide use lately in air 
defense troops in repelling enemy air strikes. That method of 
employing air defense weapons is practiced especially often in 
the battle to hold the security area. Use of fire ambushes 
enables, first of all, intercepting enemy aircraft and 
helicopters on approaches to the defense; and secondly, tying in 
operations of air defense weapons more closely with operations 
of forward detachments. Based on exercise experience, the 
following were methods of interworking of roving ambushes. 
Several SAM and AAA subunits usually were assigned to combat 
enemy aircraft in each grouping of air defense troops and were 
disposed throughout the depth of the security area. Their 
mission was to deliver surprise attacks periodically against 
airborne targets entering their zone of fire and to cover 
defending subunits. Immediately after firing, the air defense 
subunit would covertly displace to other positions chosen in 
advance and which had had engineer preparation. Constant subunit 
maneuvering in combination with the presence of dummy positions 
and simulation of activity reduced the effectiveness of enemy 
reconnaissance, thereby misleading him. 
  Coordinating the efforts of aviation and combat arms to 
inflict damage on the enemy on distant approaches to the defense 
presents a special complication for commanders and staffs of 
defending troops in organizing interworking. The effectiveness 
of interworking in performing this mission is determined by the 
ability to forecast the nature of an attacker's operations when 
moving from forming-up places up to the final coordination line, 
and determining the targets against which strikes should be 
delivered and what personnel and equipment must be used for 
this. The priority of targets should be established in this case 
based on the following sequence. Above all it is necessary to 
try to reduce the enemy's nuclear and fire-delivery potential by 
destroying means of nuclear attack and combat complexes of 
precision weapons, disrupting the system for command and control 
of weapons and troops, and destroying airmobile forces and army 
aviation. With personnel and equipment available, the mission is 
assigned to disrupt the enemy's forward movement and organized 
assault. 
  Delivery of nuclear and fire strikes against a 
forward-moving 
enemy grouping is tied in by time and place with remote mining 
of terrain, so the obstacles and destruction being created cause 
troops to concentrate and thereby help increase enemy losses. As 
the attacker's offensive grouping approaches the FEBA, it is 
important to try to ensure that the intensity of the fire effect 
grows continuously, initially by bringing in army aviation and 
long-range artillery and then by massing close-combat weapons, 
including by maneuvering them from other axes. 
  More and more importance is now attached to operations by 
covering troops in the fight for the tactical defensive zone. 
The defender's mission is to do everything necessary to turn the 
security area into a forward defensive zone. Some forward 
detachments unquestionably are incapable of achieving this goal. 
In order for them to be able to delay the forward movement of 
enemy units and inflict losses on them, it is necessary to 
support their operations by air strikes and artillery fire and 
to make wide use of various obstacles. 
  Wresting the fire initiative from the enemy is one of the 
defenders' difficult tasks. It is possible to achieve this if 
all weapons of the defense are used in coordination under a 
single plan and a single leadership. It is especially important 
to ensure immediate destruction of fast-acting enemy precision 
weapons and attack assets immediately after they are detected. 
The selection of weapons and methods of their actions depends on 
the target type and characteristics, its protection, and 
conditions of mission performance. 
  As shown by the experience of Operation Desert Storm, base 
airfields, missile launch positions, ground command and control 
facilities and operational-tactical missile launchers have high 
survivability even with the effect of precision weapon systems 
against them. Combating enemy reconnaissance-strike complexes 
possessing high accuracy, high reconnaissance reliability, high 
speed, high accuracy of dispensing homing-head-equipped 
submunitions against targets, and long range presents special 
difficulty. 
  Combating reconnaissance-strike complexes represents a 
combination of interrelated measures of reconnaissance and their 
swift destruction. It is conducted by all available means to 
prevent or hamper the complexes from affecting friendly troops 
and to win fire superiority over the enemy. In organizing combat 
against reconnaissance-strike complexes, it is important to take 
their vulnerable aspects into account: Their electronic 
equipment's susceptibility to the effect of electronic jamming; 
difficulty for radar reconnaissance assets to recognize real 
ground targets; possibility of diverting homing munitions 
(missiles) to false targets and decoys; and decreased 
capabilities for detecting ground targets and decreased accuracy 
of guiding munitions (missiles) to them when the enemy takes 
maskirovka measures. 
  Efforts by personnel and assets in organizing combat against 
enemy reconnaissance-strike complexes are coordinated to ensure 
their prompt detection and destruction. Main efforts are 
concentrated here on destroying ground command and control 
centers; reconnaissance and vectoring (relay) aircraft as well 
as strike aircraft in the air and on airfields; missile 
launchers at launch positions, when changing positions and in 
concentration areas; and guided aerial bombs and air-to-surface 
guided missiles. Prompt detection and preemptive destruction of 
enemy reconnaissance-strike complexes are achieved by collecting 
necessary intelligence and communicating it to commanders and 
staffs in a short time, by making substantiated decisions for 
their destruction, by rapidly assigning missions to troops, and 
by organizing precise interworking and command and control of 
forces and assets in the process of their destruction. 
  In coordinating combat efforts of assets being used to 
combat 
reconnaissance-strike complexes, it is important to achieve 
their comprehensive employment by inflicting fire damage on the 
reconnaissance-strike complexes simultaneously with electronic 
suppression of their control systems and also with the capture 
and destruction or disabling of their ground elements by 
motorized rifle, tank, airborne, air-assault and reconnaissance 
subunits. A necessary condition for effective combat against 
reconnaissance-strike complexes is continuous weapon effect on 
them. This requires constantly conducting effective 
reconnaissance and inflicting damage on their elements on the 
ground and in the air under all situation conditions in the 
course of the entire battle, taking advantage of the maximum 
reach of existing weapons. 
  Staff duties in preparing data for the commander for 
organizing interworking to combat enemy reconnaissance-strike 
complexes include the following: Ascertaining what procedure the 
senior commander has established for engaging 
reconnaissance-strike complexes, what personnel and equipment 
are being assigned for this, and what requires final 
reconnaissance in the enemy grouping and by what time; 
calculating the detail of personnel and assets necessary for 
combating reconnaissance-strike complexes; outlining the 
procedure for coordinating efforts of aircraft, artillery, and 
air defense and EW assets in performing that mission; 
determining possible missions and procedure of operations of 
airborne assault forces and of raiding, enveloping, 
reconnaissance and air assault detachments for capture or 
destruction of ground elements of the reconnaissance-strike 
complexes; and also determining who supports their operations 
when and how, and the signals for mutual recognition and target 
designation. 
  In organizing interworking of personnel and assets assigned 
for combating reconnaissance-strike complexes, the formation 
commander clarifies the following: Capabilities of aviation for 
reconnoitering and engaging them, sorties allocated for this, 
and time and methods for delivering strikes; missions assigned 
to artillery for destroying ground elements of 
reconnaissance-strike complexes, the makeup of personnel and 
assets used for this, and the procedure for them to perform the 
assigned mission; procedure for using air defense personnel and 
assets for destroying airborne elements of reconnaissance-strike 
complexes, methods of their operations, and procedure for 
interworking with aircraft; and capabilities of EW personnel and 
assets to suppress electronic targets of enemy 
reconnaissance-strike complexes and the procedure for their 
interworking with other personnel and assets assigned to combat 
those complexes. 
  Interworking is organized with special thoroughness in the 
fight to hold the main defensive zone. Stability and 
aggressiveness of the defense are ensured by a number of 
factors, above all by use of methods of aligning the defense, 
use of troop groupings, and their conduct of defensive 
operations appropriate to the situation. In one instance this 
will be achieved by firmly holding occupied lines in combination 
with counterattacks by troops from the depth, in another case by 
using mobile methods of warfare, and in a third case by their 
combination. 
  Coordinated operations of motorized rifle and tank units and 
subunits with artillery and with air defense and engineer units 
and subunits and aviation are of decisive importance both in a 
positional and a mobile defense. The principal objective of the 
interworking troops is to nullify the enemy's quantitative and 
qualitative superiority, impose one's will on the enemy by 
aggressive operations and use of new, nonstandard procedures, 
and wear down and exhaust his offensive grouping. Efforts of 
defending troops must be built up at a preemptive rate so it is 
possible to promptly close breaches that have formed by means of 
a fire concentration; by forward movement of antitank reserves, 
mobile obstacle detachments, and subunits removed from secondary 
axes; and also by remote mining of the terrain. 
  Combat helicopters play an important role in timely 
concentration of fire efforts on threatened axes. In organizing 
interworking with them it is necessary to make full use of their 
advantages such as the absence of a need for specially prepared 
landing sites, the capability for conducting combat operations 
regardless of terrain relief and presence of obstacles, 
capability for swift maneuver, high accuracy (probability of 
killing the target with the first launch of missiles), use of 
the factor of surprise, sudden appearance from behind cover when 
in a hover mode, capability for multipurpose use, employment of 
main weapons whose radius of action exceeds the range of the 
majority of tactical air defense systems, and the capability of 
combat employment with very low cloud cover. 
  But employment of helicopters also has substantial 
shortcomings: Lengthy time in a hover mode and the resultant 
high probability of the helicopter being killed by various kinds 
of weapons; the action of many guided missile systems from a 
distance no closer than 400-500 m; total or partial 
unsuitability of helicopters for all-weather use; practical 
impossibility even of a temporary seizure of terrain sectors by 
a helicopter subunit; limited conditions of visibility (absence 
of all-around view); and weapon effectiveness only in the 
absence of jamming. 
  The experience of local wars shows that so-called helicopter 
"roving elements" operating with motorized infantry and tank 
subunits are very effective in performing such missions as 
closing breaches, securing flanks, covering gaps and combating 
enemy raiding and enveloping detachments. Apache, Lynx-3 and 
Gazelle fire support helicopters and Black Hawk, Iroquois and 
Lynx AH-1 multipurpose helicopters with motorized infantry and 
combat engineer subunits aboard usually are included as part of 
such elements. For continuous fire effect on the enemy for the 
entire period of combat operations it is envisaged employing the 
"one-third" principle: One subunit attacks the enemy; a second 
is en route to deliver a fire strike or is en route after its 
execution; and the third is at a forward ammunition resupply and 
refueling point. 
  In examining the problem of interworking in modern defensive 
battle, it is impossible to ignore the circumstance that, in 
contrast to the past, one now has to coordinate efforts of 
defending troops in such a way as to have an opportunity to 
successfully combat enemy units and subunits which have been 
landed or have penetrated to the rear of friendly troops while 
simultaneously repelling an enemy frontal assault. To this end 
appropriate measures are envisaged, first of all, for detecting 
a landing of enemy airborne assault forces and raiding and 
reconnaissance units and a penetration into the rear of 
defending troops by his raiding, forward and enveloping 
detachments; and secondly, for disrupting their performance of 
missions and destroying them. 
  During the Great Patriotic War the enemy usually was fought 
in the depth of the friendly troop disposition by the 
territorial principle, i.e., commanders of combined arms units 
and chiefs of rear facilities were given responsibility for 
destroying enemy airborne assault forces and subunits which had 
penetrated their assigned areas of responsibility, which if 
necessary were divided into sectors and the latter into sections 
combining important facilities and their defending troops within 
their boundaries. Additional subunits would be assigned if 
necessary to reinforce the defending troops for "sweeping" the 
terrain. 
  The territorial principle of combating the enemy in the rear 
of friendly troops in the defense retains its importance even 
under present conditions. This obligates units and subunits to 
be ready to destroy enemy airborne assault forces and other 
units regardless of their place in the combat formation. But in 
addition, performing this mission also requires the assignment 
of special antilanding reserves, reinforcing them with 
artillery, combat helicopters and engineer subunits. In 
coordinating efforts of antilanding forces, it is important to 
tie their actions in with airborne and ground surveillance 
posts, various patrols, traffic control posts and air defense 
weapons in order to detect the appearance of enemy units 
promptly, warn friendly troops of this and take steps to destroy 
them without delay. 
  Organizing interworking presents the greatest difficulty in 
the dynamics of defensive battle when combat efforts of 
defending troops are to be transferred from one position or line 
to another, i.e., with transition from a positional to a mobile 
defense. The uniqueness of conditions in this case consists of 
the extraordinary dynamic nature and intensity of the situation. 
Having the initiative, the enemy can make wide use of close and 
deep envelopments to cut off and encircle withdrawing subunits, 
land airborne assault forces in their rear, and make deep 
penetrations to preempt defending troops in moving to favorable 
lines in the depth. 
  In coordinating efforts of units and subunits under these 
conditions, it is important to ensure that the main body breaks 
contact with the attacker; and to tie him up for a certain time 
with battles in the space between positions by means of 
aggressive actions of covering subunits, skilled use of mobile 
antitank subunits and helicopter and ground ambushes, and the 
conduct of surprise counterattacks even with forces of small 
subunits, as well as by emplacing obstacles primarily by remote 
minelaying equipment. Strikes by missile troops and aircraft, 
and artillery fire from indirect firing positions are organized 
so as to ensure engagement of the enemy from maximum ranges, 
prevent his approach, deployment and preparation for an assault, 
counter deep and close envelopments, and, most important, win 
time and achieve a timely maneuver of withdrawing subunits to 
occupy a favorable line in the depth. 
  The art of organizing interworking in conducting a mobile 
defense lies in inflicting damage with limited personnel and 
equipment on an enemy who is many times superior in personnel 
and equipment; winning time; placing enemy troops in difficult 
conditions, hampering their maneuver and at the same time 
conserving one's own forces; being able to move troops out from 
under an enemy attack in time; drawing the attacker into fire 
pockets or under attack from ambushes; and misleading him 
regarding one's true intentions by deception procedures. 
<H3>  3. Principle of Interworking in Offensive Battle and the 
Meeting Engagement </H3>
  The procedure developed in the Great Patriotic War for 
coordinating combat efforts of troops in the offensive retains 
its significance even under present conditions. The 1989 
"Boyevoy ustav Sukhoputnykh voysk" [Ground Troops Field Manual] 
states that interworking should be organized by missions, lines, 
time and methods of mission execution.[.sup]38[/] With 
respect to the content of interworking, procedures for its 
organization, and work methods of command and control entities, 
much has changed here compared with the past both in the defense 
as well as in the offensive battle and meeting engagement under 
the influence of new factors of warfare which appeared in 
postwar times. 
  The sequence of developing questions of interworking in 
combined arms battle is shown in Fig. 13. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-71A>             Fig. 13. Sequence of developing questions ofFigure 1. Artillery Battalion </FIG>



  In analyzing the system of troop interworking established in 
the past war, it is easy to note that a certain method was 
inherent to it. This reflected the planned nature of conducting 
the offensive. It would begin during breakthrough of the enemy 
defense with artillery and air preparation of the assault, and 
included the successive taking of the first, second and 
subsequent defensive positions. Troop combat efforts would build 
up during the battle for them. Then the troops would exploit the 
success achieved and shift to the pursuit under favorable 
conditions (Fig. 14). Thus, troop combat efforts would be 
coordinated for these and similar individual missions. 




    Now the attacker strives to deliver deep strikes at the very 
beginning of battle, take in the entire enemy tactical defensive 
zone with aggressive combat operations, immobilize all elements 
of his combat alignment, transfer combat efforts into the depth 
as quickly as possible, and establish a constantly operating 
front in the enemy rear by landing the air echelon there and by 
the swift penetration of forward units and of raiding and 
enveloping detachments. It is understandable that this method of 
the offensive predetermines methods of coordinating combat 
efforts of elements of the combat formation of combat arms units 
differently than before, inasmuch as they have to operate 
dispersed across a broad front and to a great depth in 
performing diverse missions. 
  A flexible "multiechelon" system of interworking should 
correspond to that character of the land-air battle. In 
organizing it, commanders and staffs must take into account the 
possibility of the sides' deep mutual penetrations, conduct of 
battle with an "inverted" front, and a rapid, abrupt transition 
from one kind of combat operations to another, which 
predetermines continuous correction of the battle plan and the 
system of interworking. 
  Under those conditions commanders and staff officers should 
display profound tactical prudence, anticipate how combat events 
might develop, what resistance the enemy will offer in the 
battle for a particular objective, and what new combat 
procedures and kinds of weapons he may employ; accordingly, they 
should determine how to use the attack and maneuver capabilities 
of friendly combat arms more effectively and how to tie their 
actions in with each other so it is possible to make up for weak 
aspects of one kind of weapon with strong aspects of others. 
  In view of the fact that frequent "interruptions" in the 
system of interworking are possible in the course of battle 
either due to enemy effect on advancing troops or due to 
subordinates' imprecise actions and inability to organize, it is 
important to react to situation changes exceptionally swiftly, 
take prompt measures preventing disruption of the prescribed 
procedure for coordinated actions, update missions for subunits, 
and correctly determine the primary importance of a particular 
combat arm in achieving success so as to involve all other 
forces and assets in support of its operations. 
  It is impossible to ignore the fact that many 
military-theoretical works give the recommendation that 
interworking in the offensive should be organized in greatest 
detail to the depth of performance of the immediate 
mission.[.sup]39[/] It would appear that this approach to 
coordinating efforts does not fully reflect the altered 
conditions of modern battle, which has become deep and vast, in 
connection with which it is difficult to factor out where the 
primary mission is being accomplished. While in the past, when 
the capture of enemy defensive positions was the basis of 
attacking troops' combat missions and the range of the bulk of 
division and regimental weapons was relatively short, the 
provisions indicated above for planning battle in detail only to 
a shallow depth were fully justified. Now the situation has 
changed. 
  The grouping of enemy weapons has become the basis of the 
defense, which largely predetermines its stability. It is 
impossible to disrupt the defensive system without having 
destroyed this grouping. But for this it is necessary to deliver 
strikes both against his close-range as well as long-range 
weapons simultaneously. Consequently, in preparing the offensive 
it is advisable to plan interworking in all details essentially 
to the full depth of the combat mission. This will enable 
interworking commanders and staffs to correctly calculate their 
personnel and equipment and distribute the available resource of 
ammunition, fuels and lubricants and other supplies for the 
entire period of battle. 
  Many new requirements for organization of reconnaissance of 
the enemy defense, discovery of his deep targets, a larger-scale 
situation estimate, thorough performance of operational-tactical 
calculations and simulation of combat operations stem from what 
has been said. Inasmuch as the system of defense alignment now 
largely has changed and main troop efforts are concentrated on 
holding not so much positions as vital areas (which is where the 
main weapons as well as follow-on forces are concentrated), it 
is necessary to coordinate the operations of attacking units and 
subunits not only by lines and objectives, but also by the most 
important areas whose capture will ensure undermining of the 
stability of the entire defensive system of an enemy formation 
or unit. 
  Major changes in the nature of modern battle dictated by 
employment of new weapons demand determining the sequence of 
coordinating troop combat efforts by individual missions 
differently than before. Thus, previously organization of 
interworking would begin with the tying in of operations in the 
period of artillery and air preparation of the assault. 
Preparatory measures preceding this were left outside the 
framework of the interworking process. This was explained by the 
fact that the offensive against a deliberate enemy defense was 
carried out as a rule from a position occupied in immediate 
contact with the enemy, and only in rare cases did the latter 
have an opportunity to strike an offensive troop grouping poised 
for an assault by conducting artillery and air 
counterpreparation and thereby disrupting the assault. 
  Now the danger of an offensive being disrupted has increased 
considerably and this circumstance is impossible to ignore, 
especially as troops may launch an offensive not only from a 
position of defense, but also often while moving forward from 
forming-up places occupied in the depth or from the march. But 
it is common knowledge that troop vulnerability to enemy 
precision weapons is especially high during forward movement, as 
they are not under cover. And in an offensive, the danger of 
troops being hit if the defender delivers fire strikes also 
increases, especially at the moment they launch an assault. 
  With consideration of this, it appears advisable to take 
measures aimed at preventing the enemy from disrupting an 
offensive. This task is very difficult and many-sided. Its 
accomplishment presumes coordination of efforts of all 
interworking personnel and equipment so as to ensure effective 
fire and electronic countermeasures to enemy weapons, reliable 
fire cover from the ground and from the air for troops moving 
forward, their swift negotiation of obstacles created by enemy 
remote minelaying equipment, and combat against enemy airborne 
assault forces, tactical airmobile detachments and raiding and 
reconnaissance units being landed on routes of forward movement 
and in the rear of attacking troops. It is important to ensure 
high survivability and protection of subunits against strikes by 
the defender's precision weapon systems and rapid restoration of 
troop combat effectiveness in case they are subjected to enemy 
nuclear and fire strikes. 
  In coordinating actions of units and subunits in the process 
of forward movement, deployment and launching an assault, it is 
necessary to take into account the range and effectiveness of 
enemy weapons which may bring pressure on forward-moving units. 
Timely engagement of those weapons whose impact zone they 
successively enter as they approach the FEBA should be envisaged 
for this. Above all it is necessary to destroy ground and 
airborne elements of reconnaissance-strike complexes, missile 
launchers, MLRS, combat helicopters on pads, field artillery 
employing guided munitions, ATGM systems and other antitank 
weapons, especially armored targets. Simultaneously, one should 
coordinate efforts of missile troops and artillery with aviation 
for engaging personnel and weapons in company or platoon 
strongpoints during fire preparation and then also during fire 
support of an assault by motorized rifle and tank subunits. 
  In coordinating efforts of troops moving forward for 
combating enemy airborne assault forces, their possible landing 
areas are determined, necessary antilanding forces are assigned, 
and helicopter ambushes are arranged whose operations are tied 
in with air strikes and artillery fire and also with actions of 
forward-moving motorized rifle and tank subunits. In determining 
the procedure for negotiating mass obstacles created by the 
enemy in the period of the troops' forward movement, it is 
necessary to take into account when and by what method he may 
emplace them. Surprise "straddling" of subunits' combat or march 
formation by remote minelaying equipment presents special danger. 
  It must be borne in mind that all remotely laid mines have 
safety devices preventing premature initiation. Many are armed 
5-8 minutes after falling to the ground. With the presence of 
such devices confirmed and the type of mines determined, the 
best method of troop actions is their immediate departure from 
the mined area without clearing lanes; but a halt can be made if 
the opportunity presents itself. Being in a mined area even for 
a short time (2-4 hours) may reduce losses from exploding mines, 
since after a certain time the mines' self-destruction 
(neutralization) elements are triggered. In the course of 
forward movement one should expect minelaying by the "straddle" 
method in route sectors where going around them is difficult (in 
chokepoints, in defiles, on crossings). In this case organizing 
duties of observation and warning of mine danger assumes special 
importance. 
  In coordinating troop combat efforts to counter enemy 
weapons 
which may disrupt or hamper the operations of attacking 
subunits, it is necessary on the one hand to take steps to 
promptly detect enemy fire control facilities, aircraft 
vectoring posts, ground and airborne elements of 
reconnaissance-strike and reconnaissance-fire complexes, 
position areas of missile troops, artillery firing positions and 
helicopter landing sites; and on the other hand to ensure the 
readiness and capability of friendly weapons for immediate, 
effective pressure on the above. 
  Along with active methods of troop operations aimed at 
preventing enemy disruption of an offensive, in organizing 
interworking one also cannot lose sight of the need for carrying 
out such measures as ensuring covertness of the offensive and 
survivability of subunits. To this end, in choosing routes of 
forward movement make maximum use of the terrain's protective 
and concealing features. Optical and radar dead ground formed by 
relief and local features can be used for protecting equipment 
moving along prepared routes against enemy precision weapon 
systems, while heat-emitting and radar decoys are set up along 
routes in sectors capable of being observed. Meanwhile, it is 
advisable to prepare dummy routes, and radar reflectors should 
be set up in their open sectors. 
  Efforts of interworking personnel and equipment should be 
coordinated with special thoroughness to achieve an organized, 
resolute assault of the enemy FEBA. This is the culmination of 
battle. The defender will strive to commit the maximum of 
close-range and long-range weapons to bring pressure on 
assaulting subunits. One can judge the intensity of his fire at 
this moment from the fact that just with organic weapons a 
defending motorized infantry battalion can use more than 300 
weapons of various kinds for repulsing an assault, including 
over 100 long-range antitank weapons capable of hitting armored 
targets beginning from ranges of 3,000-4,000 m. 
  Hence the need arises to coordinate employment of friendly 
weapons so as to subject weapons situated not only on the enemy 
FEBA, but also in the depth to simultaneous pressure. But this 
requires reconnoitering the defensive system and having precise 
knowledge of the location of each dug-in tank, gun and IFV as 
well as ATGM. To ensure a successful assault it is necessary to 
destroy at least 70-80 percent of antitank weapons right during 
fire preparation. 
  The procedure for engaging enemy targets at his first 
defensive position and in the depth may be as follows. Armored 
antitank weapons situated immediately in front of assaulting 
subunits and on flanks of the penetration sector are destroyed 
by the fire of artillery pieces, ATGM systems and combat 
helicopters. At the same time, aircraft and MLRS strikes are 
delivered against the following situated in the defensive depth: 
Enemy tanks and antitank subunits (with ATGM systems on an 
armored base), MLRS batteries, and antitank helicopter subunits 
at their bases. Combat helicopters play an important role in 
destroying armored targets and other targets in the enemy 
defense during an assault. In organizing interworking with them, 
the combined arms commander indicates when and against which 
targets to deliver a strike; the procedure for mutual 
recognition of friendly subunits; and target designation 
signals. Helicopter subunits can deliver simultaneous strikes at 
full strength or with the bulk of forces against preassigned 
targets at a designated time, or successive strikes against 
targets newly detected in the course of an assault, with 
departure on call from an alert status at staging sites, from 
ambushes, or from airborne alert. With a sharply changing ground 
situation, intensive enemy electronic jamming, and with reliable 
suppression of his air defense weapons, helicopters may carry 
out an independent target search (target-of-opportunity roving). 
Here is how this was done in exercises. 
  A pair of fire support helicopters usually was assigned for 
a 
search. The distance between them in depth was 1,000-1,500 m 
with the very same altitude. On detecting a target, the 
helicopters would deliver a strike against it and if necessary 
would call in a reinforcing element and vector it to the strike 
target. Helicopters would make a target approach from a 
favorable direction which ensured covertness of the approach, 
reliable detection and recognition of the target, and a swift 
attack. Best conditions for a surprise strike were created with 
an approach to the target below the lower limit of the impact 
zone of air defense systems, which is possible when flying at an 
extremely low altitude (20-30 m) and taking advantage of folds 
of the terrain. With heavy enemy air defense, helicopters would 
engage the enemy while above friendly subunit combat formations. 
  Based on experience of combat operations in Afghanistan, 
combat helicopters would employ the following methods of attack 
-- from level flight, a dive, or a hover. 
  An attack from level flight would be made for engaging 
targets with ATGM's and free-flight rockets. Duration of the 
strike was shortened and its effectiveness was achieved when 
helicopters employed the maximum number of weapons in one pass. 
Helicopters would deliver strikes without going beyond limits of 
the disposition of friendly subunit combat formations. 
  An attack from a dive was executed for hitting targets with 
free-flight rockets, but here the range to the target did not 
exceed 1,000-1,500 m. With weak opposition from enemy air 
defense weapons, such an attack was used to hit targets situated 
in folds of the terrain, in shelters, and behind reverse 
hillslopes, i.e., when an attack from level flight proved 
impossible. 
  A helicopter attack from a hover is the most effective. In a 
hover mode the helicopter can employ all kinds of weapons 
(ATGM's, free-flight rockets) and conduct machinegun fire. The 
helicopter must change its position after each launch in a hover 
mode. 
  The experience of the Great Patriotic War and local wars 
showed that greatest difficulties in maintaining interworking 
are created during battle in the depth of the enemy defense, 
which is characterized by unpredictability of the development of 
events and the frequent appearance of crisis situations. Far 
from everything can be anticipated in advance in operations of 
combat formation elements and combat arms before the beginning 
of an offensive. Therefore one must be ready for the fact that 
in the course of battle it will be necessary to substantially 
correct or even create the system of interworking anew more than 
once. 
  It can be expected that as attacking troops wedge into the 
defense, the enemy will step up resistance and do everything 
possible to localize the penetration. Therefore in the course of 
battle there will be a stubborn contest of the sides in building 
up combat efforts. Under such conditions, preempting the enemy 
in maneuvering and in delivering fire strikes and disrupting his 
plan are of great importance. It is important not to give him an 
opportunity to restore a disrupted fire and obstacle plan or to 
carry out a planned redeployment of personnel and assets 
laterally and out of the depth. Successful performance of these 
and other missions by the attacking troops largely depends on 
coordination of their operations by objective, place and time. 
  It is especially important to achieve precision and 
cohesiveness of troop operations in building up combat efforts 
on a decisive axis, i.e., where success has appeared. 
  Above all a commander must decide on the method by which he 
should strive to continuously maintain decisive superiority over 
the enemy on the main axis. It is common knowledge that in World 
War II essentially the only method of building up efforts was to 
commit second echelons or reserves. Now the prevailing place is 
held by fire strikes of reconnaissance-strike and 
reconnaissance-fire complexes, missile troops, and aviation and 
by artillery fire. The advantage of this method lies in 
swiftness of execution. 
  In addition, at the present time there has been a 
considerable expansion in troop capabilities for building up 
efforts by employing airborne assault forces and airmobile 
subunits. Landed in the depth of the enemy defense right after 
fire strikes, they are capable of quickly exploiting their 
results, capturing tactically important areas (road junctions, 
commanding heights, passes, built-up areas, crossings over water 
obstacles) and thereby preventing the approach of enemy reserves 
and contributing to exploitation of the success of first echelon 
units. 
  At crisis moments of battle, when there is the threat that 
the offensive will "lose steam" or even be disrupted, the 
commander will have to use all forces and assets at his disposal 
to retain the initiative, i.e., he must build up efforts both by 
a maneuver of fire as well as by commitment of the second 
echelon or reserve, and if possible also by landing an assault 
force in the enemy rear. It is necessary to achieve coordinated 
delivery of strikes against the defense simultaneously from the 
ground and air and from the front, flanks and rear in order to 
dissipate the enemy's attention and efforts. 
  This is a difficult task. By the time the second echelon is 
committed, the situation often can become critical as a result 
of the enemy's delivery of a surprise, stunning strike. It is 
not precluded that command and control will be disrupted and 
that some units and subunits will lose combat effectiveness. 
Under those conditions steps are taken above all to determine 
the true status of troops and restore disrupted command and 
control. The combat mission is updated for the commander of the 
subunit being committed and he is also told the point of 
commitment to battle, routes and time for moving to it, and 
procedure for fire support and interworking with first echelon 
subunits. If an airborne assault force is landed in the enemy 
rear and the dispatch of a raiding detachment is planned 
simultaneously with commitment of the second echelon, then their 
operations are coordinated by objective, place and time. 
  Under favorable conditions it is advisable to create smoke 
screens to ensure concealment of the second echelon's 
commitment. The procedure for employing smokes can vary. 
Blinding smoke screens in support of assaulting motorized rifle 
and tank subunits usually are laid down by artillery in terrain 
sectors easily viewed from the enemy's side at the point of 
commitment to battle. Blinding of the defender's antitank 
weapons and tanks by artillery smoke projectiles should begin 
3-5 minutes before the end of a fire assault and end with the 
arrival of assaulting subunits at the final coordination line. 
  Concealing smoke screens can be emplaced in the course of 
battle by the assaulting subunits themselves to hamper 
operations of enemy antitank helicopters and also to conceal a 
maneuver. Smoke generation begins with the subunits' arrival in 
the impact zone of enemy ATGM's or at the final coordination 
line. When the subunits approach the smoke screening line, smoke 
generation ceases and the assault is carried out. The experience 
of local wars shows that the effectiveness of employing enemy 
antitank weapons is reduced by 3-5 times with skillful use of 
concealing smoke screens and by 10-15 times when using blinding 
screens. It is advisable to use smoke assets suddenly across a 
broad front with consideration of terrain and weather conditions. 
  In conducting battle in the depth of the enemy defense, 
motorized rifle and tank units should interwork with aviation 
with special precision. The fact is that in a number of cases 
because of a lag, artillery will be the only means of troop 
support. Coordination of air and ground strikes on the 
battlefield is manifested in distributing targets between 
artillery and aviation, in establishing the priority of attacks 
between aircraft and helicopters, and in designating lines of 
responsibility. Safety measures are strictly observed. 
  In coordinating combat efforts of motorized rifle and tank 
units and artillery with aviation, the principle implemented is 
that aviation attacks those targets whose destruction by ground 
troops' weapons is hampered or impossible. Ground and air 
strikes are tied in by time and lines. Efforts of artillery, 
combat helicopters and aircraft are separated by time and lines. 
During the day the line of permissible air attack comes closer 
to the FEBA and at night it pulls back. Aircraft and helicopter 
flights are staggered in altitude and they are assigned routes 
by a joint air traffic control center. Fire support of front 
aviation, combat helicopters and artillery is directed according 
to a schedule compiled and coordinated in detail. 
  Experience gained in local wars and tactical exercises 
permits drawing certain conclusions with respect to 
characteristic shortcomings allowed by combined arms commanders 
in organizing and accomplishing interworking with aviation. 
Above all there often is a tendency to dissipate air efforts to 
combat numerous small targets instead of concentrating strikes 
against the most important objectives. Sometimes the role of 
long-range artillery is imposed on combat aircraft, i.e., they 
are assigned missions for engaging targets situated at a shallow 
depth. The principle of economy of allocated air sorties is not 
always adhered to; they are quickly used up when units perform 
the immediate mission and no sorties remain for supporting 
subsequent operations. It also often happens that, having called 
in aircraft to deliver a strike against one target, the combined 
arms commander changes their mission and strike targets when 
aircraft appear over the battlefield, as a result of which 
neither mission is executed. A shortcoming such as poor 
intelligence support to aviation also is typical. The air 
command element often is forced to conduct reconnaissance "for 
itself" and to concern itself with vectoring aircraft to 
designated targets and about their markings. 
  In conclusion, we will dwell on certain features of 
interworking in a meeting engagement. Above all we will note 
that usually it is organized under conditions of extremely 
limited time during the march, which requires high efficiency 
and cohesiveness in work of commanders and staffs and swiftness 
and precision of troop operations. General principles for 
organizing interworking are the very same as in the offensive. 
The distinction is that missions for units and subunits and the 
system of interworking must be updated more often. Special 
attention in coordinating troop combat efforts is given to 
preempting the enemy in deploying, opening fire and executing a 
maneuver. 
<H5>  Conclusions and Recommendations </H5>
  1. The principle of interworking is one of the fundamental 
principles of combined arms battle. It indicates that to achieve 
the assigned goal--to defeat the enemy--it is necessary to 
ensure precise operations of all personnel and assets 
participating in the battle, strictly coordinated by missions, 
axes, lines, time and methods of conducting battle. 
  2. Organization and accomplishment of interworking is a 
complex, many-sided, creative process of the commander and staff 
officers which requires them to have profound foresight of the 
development of events and the ability to effectively use fire, 
attack and maneuver capabilities of units and subunits of combat 
arms and special troops under various situation conditions, to 
closely tie their actions in with each other, and to make up for 
weak aspects and shortcomings of some with the strong aspects 
and advantages of other combat arms and special troops in order 
to successfully perform the combat mission by joint, coordinated 
efforts. 
  3. Fundamentals of interworking are laid down in the 
commander's decision, but interworking does not duplicate the 
decision; it develops and supplements it. While the important 
thing in the decision is to determine the objective of battle 
and methods of achieving it, the most important thing in 
organizing interworking is determine specific ways of fulfilling 
assigned missions with consideration of possible situation 
changes, different options of operations by friendly and enemy 
troops, and the appearance of crisis situations. 
  4. Although fundamentals of interworking in battle which 
were 
developed in the Great Patriotic War retain their significance 
even now, continuous renewal of the material base of modern 
battle requires searching for new ways of realizing this 
principle with consideration of demands of deep, air-ground, 
electronic battle characterized by an ever growing spatial 
scope, dynamic nature, high decisiveness and mobility. 
  5. To master proficiency in organizing interworking, 
officers 
are required to continuously deepen their knowledge in studying 
the nature and character of modern combined arms battle, combat 
capabilities of weapons and combat equipment, and methods of 
their employment in battle; develop tactical prudence and skills 
in performing operational-tactical calculations and modeling 
combat operations; and be able to quickly collect situation data 
and restore a disrupted system of communications and system of 
interworking. 
